{"title_page": "Beluga whale", "text_new": "{{redirect|White Whale}}\n{{Other uses|Beluga (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|Species of whale}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|3.6|0|[[Quaternary]]\u2013Recent}}\n| name = Beluga whale<ref name=msw3>{{MSW3 Cetacea|id=14300105|page=735}}</ref>\n| image = Beluga03.jpg\n| image_alt = A beluga whale\n| image_caption = At [[Georgia Aquarium]]\n| image2 = Beluga size.svg\n| image2_alt = Size comparison to an average human\n| image2_caption = Size compared to an average human\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref name=iucn />\n| genus = Delphinapterus\n| parent_authority = [[Bernard Germain de Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de|Lac\u00e9p\u00e8de]], 1804\n| species = leucas\n| authority = ([[Peter Simon Pallas|Pallas]], 1776)\n| range_map = Cetacea range map Beluga.png\n| range_map_caption = Beluga range\n}}\n\nThe '''beluga whale''' ({{IPAc-en|b|\u026a|\u02c8|l|u\u02d0|\u0261|\u0259}}) (''Delphinapterus leucas'') is an Arctic and sub-Arctic [[cetacean]]. It is one of two members of the family [[Monodontidae]], along with the [[narwhal]], and the only member of the [[genus]] ''Delphinapterus''. It is also known as the '''white whale''', as it is the only cetacean of this colour; the '''sea canary''', due to its high-pitched calls; and the '''melonhead''', though that more commonly refers to the [[melon-headed whale]], which is an [[oceanic dolphin]].\n\nThe beluga is adapted to life in the Arctic, so it has anatomical and physiological characteristics that differentiate it from other cetaceans. Amongst these are its all-white colour and the absence of a [[dorsal fin]], which allows them to swim under ice with ease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/55466-beluga-whales.html|title=Facts About Beluga Whales|last=Bradford|first=Alina|last2=July 19|first2=Live Science Contributor {{!}}|website=Live Science|access-date=2019-06-12|last3=ET|first3=2016 08:45pm}}</ref> It possesses a distinctive protuberance at the front of its head which houses an [[animal echolocation|echolocation organ]] called the [[Melon (whale)|melon]], which in this species is large and deformable. The beluga's body size is between that of a dolphin and a true whale, with males growing up to {{convert|5.5|m|abbr=on}} long and weighing up to {{convert|1600|kg|-1|abbr=on}}. This whale has a stocky body. Like many cetaceans, a large percentage of its weight is [[blubber]] (subcutaneous fat). Its sense of hearing is highly developed and its [[Animal echolocation|echolocation]] allows it to move about and find breathing holes under sheet ice.\n\nBelugas are [[gregarious]] and form groups of 10 animals on average, although during the summer, they can gather in the hundreds or even thousands in [[Estuary|estuaries]] and shallow coastal areas. They are slow swimmers, but can dive to {{convert|700|m|abbr=on}} below the surface. They are [[List of feeding behaviours|opportunistic feeders]] and their diets vary according to their locations and the season. The majority of belugas live in the [[Arctic Ocean]] and the seas and coasts around North America, Russia and Greenland; their worldwide population is thought to number around 150,000. They are [[Animal migration|migratory]] and the majority of groups spend the winter around the [[Arctic ice cap]]; when the [[sea ice]] melts in summer, they move to warmer river estuaries and coastal areas. Some populations are sedentary and do not migrate over great distances during the year.\n\nThe native peoples of North America and Russia have hunted belugas for many centuries. They were also hunted by non-natives during the 19th century and part of the 20th century. Hunting of belugas is not controlled by the [[International Whaling Commission]], and each country has developed its own regulations in different years. Currently some [[Inuit]] in Canada and Greenland, [[Alaska Native]] groups and Russians are allowed to hunt belugas to consume and sell; [[aboriginal whaling]] is excluded from the [[International Whaling Commission]] 1986 moratorium on hunting. The numbers have dropped substantially in Russia and Greenland, but not in Alaska and Canada. Other threats include natural predators ([[polar bear]]s and [[killer whale]]s), contamination of rivers (as with [[Polychlorinated biphenyl]] (PCBs) which [[bioaccumulate]] up the food chain) and [[infectious disease]]s. The beluga was placed on the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]]'s [[IUCN Red List|Red List]] in 2008 as being \"near threatened\"; the subpopulation from the [[Cook Inlet]] in Alaska, however, is considered [[critically endangered]] and is under the protection of the United States' [[Endangered Species Act]]. Of seven Canadian beluga populations, those inhabiting eastern [[Hudson Bay]], [[Ungava Bay]] and the St. Lawrence River are listed as endangered.\n\nBelugas are one of the most commonly kept cetaceans in captivity and are housed in aquariums, [[dolphinarium]]s and wildlife parks in North America, Europe and Asia. They are popular with the public due to their colour and expression.\n{{toclimit|3}}\n\n== Taxonomy ==\n[[File:Narwhal x Beluga.jpg|thumb|upright|Skull of a cross between a narwhal and a beluga whale, at the Zoological Museum, Copenhagen]]\nThe beluga was first described in 1776 by [[Peter Simon Pallas]].<ref name=msw3 /> It is a member of the [[Monodontidae]] [[family (biology)|family]], which is in turn part of the [[parvorder]] [[Odontoceti]] (toothed whales).<ref name=msw3 /> The [[Irrawaddy dolphin]] was once placed in the same family, though recent genetic evidence suggests these dolphins belong to the family [[Dolphin|Delphinidae]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Arnold |first=P. |chapter=Irrawaddy Dolphin ''Orcaella brevirostris'' |chapter-url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=2rkHQpToi9sC |page=652}}|page=652|encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Marine Mammals}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Gr\u00e9tarsd\u00f3ttir, S. |author2=\u00c1rnason, \u00da. |title=Evolution of the common cetacean highly repetitive DNA component and the systematic position of ''Orcaella brevirostris'' |journal=Journal of Molecular Evolution |volume=34 |pages=201\u2013208 |doi=10.1007/BF00162969 |issue=3 |year=1992 |pmid=1588595 |bibcode=1992JMolE..34..201G}}</ref> The [[narwhal]] is the only other species within the Monodontidae besides the beluga.<ref name=encyc>{{cite encyclopedia |last=O'Corry-Crowe |first=G. |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=2rkHQpToi9sC |page=94}}|title=Beluga Whale ''Delphinapterus leucas''|pages=94\u201399 |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Marine Mammals}}</ref> A skull has been discovered with intermediate characteristics supporting the hypothesis that [[Hybrid (biology)|hybridisation]] is possible between these two families.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1748-7692.1993.tb00454.x |title=Description of an Anomalous Monodontid Skull from West Greenland: A Possible Hybrid? |year=1993 |last1=Heide-J\u00f8rgensen |first1=Mads P. |last2=Reeves |first2=Randall R. |journal=Marine Mammal Science |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=258\u201368}}</ref>\n\nThe name of the [[genus]], ''Delphinapterus'', means \"dolphin without fin\" (from the [[Greek (language)|Greek]] \u03b4\u03b5\u03bb\u03c6\u03af\u03bd (''delphin''), dolphin and \u03b1\u03c0\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 (''apteros''), without fin) and the species name ''leucas'' means \"white\" (from the Greek \u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c2 (''leukas''), white).<ref name=Leatherwood>{{cite book |last1=Leatherwood |first1=Stephen |last2=Reeves |first2=Randall R. |title=The Sierra Club Handbook of Whales and Dolphins |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=Kx4XAQAAIAAJ |page=320}}|year=1983|publisher=Sierra Club Books|isbn=978-0-87156-340-8|page=320}}</ref> The [[Red List of Threatened Species]] gives both beluga and white whale as common names, though the former is now more popular. The English name comes from the [[Russian language|Russian]] \u0431\u0435\u043b\u0443\u0445\u0430 (''belukha''), which derives from the word \u0431\u0435\u043b\u044b\u0439 (''b\u00e9lyj''), meaning \"white\".<ref name=Leatherwood /> The name ''beluga'' in Russian refers to an unrelated species, a fish, the [[Beluga (sturgeon)|beluga sturgeon]].\n\nThe whale is also colloquially known as the sea canary on account of its high-pitched squeaks, squeals, clucks and whistles. A Japanese researcher says he taught a beluga to \"talk\" by using these sounds to identify three different objects, offering hope that humans may one day be able to communicate effectively with sea mammals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meeja.com.au/index.php?display_article_id=221 |title=Japanese whale whisperer teaches beluga to talk |publisher=meeja.com.au |date=16 September 2008 |accessdate=16 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113165459/http://www.meeja.com.au/index.php?display_article_id=221 |archivedate=13 January 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> A similar observation has been made by Canadian researchers, where a beluga which died in 2007 \"talked\" when he was still a subadult. Another example is [[NOC (whale)|NOC]], a beluga whale that could mimic the rhythm and tone of human language. Beluga whales in the wild have been reported to imitate human voices.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nzz.ch/ |title=Ein \"sprechender\" Beluga-Wal |trans-title=A \"talking\" Beluga whale |author=Kusma, Stephanie |date=23 October 2012 |language=German |newspaper=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024225347/http://www.nzz.ch/ |archivedate=24 October 2012 |accessdate=25 October 2012 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Evolution ==\n{{See also|Evolution of cetaceans}}\n[[File:Squelette Delphinapterus leucas rdl.jpg|thumb|left|Skeleton of ''D. leucas'']]\n[[Mitochondrial DNA]] studies have shown modern cetaceans last shared a common ancestor between 25 and 34 million years ago<ref name=\"waddell\"/><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a025599 |title=Cytochrome b nucleotide sequences and the identification of five primary lineages of extant cetaceans |year=1996 |last1=Arnason |first1=U. |last2=Gullberg |first2=A. |journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution |volume=13 |issue=2 |pages=407\u201317 |pmid=8587505|doi-access=free }}</ref> The superfamily Delphinoidea (which contains monodontids, dolphins and porpoises) split from other toothed whales, odontoceti, between 11 and 15 million years ago. Monodontids then split from dolphins (Delphinidae) and later from [[porpoise]]s (Phocoenidae), their closest relatives in evolutionary terms.<ref name=\"waddell\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1006/mpev.1999.0751 |title=Molecular Phylogenetic Examination of the Delphinoidea Trichotomy: Congruent Evidence from Three Nuclear Loci Indicates That Porpoises (Phocoenidae) Share a More Recent Common Ancestry with White Whales (Monodontidae) Than They Do with True Dolphins (Delphinidae) |year=2000 |last1=Waddell |first1=Victor G. |last2=Milinkovitch |first2=Michel C. |last3=B\u00e9rub\u00e9 |first3=Martine |last4=Stanhope |first4=Michael J. |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=314\u20138 |pmid=10837160}}</ref> In 2017 the genome of a beluga whale was sequenced, comprising 2.327 Gbp of assembled genomic sequence that encoded 29,581 predicted genes.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3390/genes8120378 |pmid=29232881 |pmc=5748696 |title=The Genome of the Beluga Whale (''Delphinapterus leucas'') |year=2017 |last1=Jones |first1=Steven J.M.|display-authors=et al |journal=Genes |volume=8 |issue=12 |pages=378 }}</ref> The authors estimated that the genome-wide sequence similarity between beluga whales and [[killer whale]]s to be 97.87% \u00b1 2.4 \u00d7 10<sup>\u22127</sup>% (mean \u00b1 standard deviation).\n\nThe beluga's earliest known distinctive ancestors include the prehistoric ''[[Denebola brachycephala]]'' from the late Miocene epoch (9\u201310&nbsp;million years ago),<ref>{{cite book |author=Barnes, Lawrence G |title=Fossil odontocetes (Mammalia: Cetacea) from the Almejas Formation, Isla Cedros, Mexico |asin=B0006YRTU4 |publisher=University of California, Museum of Paleontology |page=46}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://zipcodezoo.com/Animals/d/denebola_brachycephala/ |title=''Denebola brachycephala'' |publisher=ZipcodeZoo.com |accessdate=1 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820200607/http://zipcodezoo.com/Animals/d/denebola_brachycephala/ |archivedate=20 August 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Bohaskaia monodontoides]]'', from the early Pliocene (3\u20135&nbsp;million years ago).<ref name=velez/> Fossil evidence from Baja California<ref>{{cite journal |author=Barnes, L. G. |title=Outline of Eastern North Pacific Fossil Cetacean Assemblages |journal=Systematic Zoology |volume=25 |year=1977 |pages=321\u2013343 |doi=10.2307/2412508 |issue=4 |jstor=2412508}}</ref> and Virginia indicate the family once inhabited warmer waters.<ref name=velez>{{cite journal | last1 = V\u00e9lez-Juarbe | first1 = J. | last2 = Pyenson | first2 = N. D. | year = 2012 | title = Bohaskaia monodontoides, a new monodontid (Cetacea, Odontoceti, Delphinoidea) from the Pliocene of the western North Atlantic Ocean | url = | journal = Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology | volume = 32 | issue = 2| pages = 476\u2013484 | doi = 10.1080/02724634.2012.641705 }}</ref> A fossil of the monodontid ''[[Casatia thermophila]]'', from five million years ago, provides the strongest evidence that monodontids once inhabited warmer waters, as the fossil was found alongside fossils of tropical species such as bull and tiger sharks.<ref>Bianucci, G., Pesci, F., Collareta, A., & Tinelli, C. (2019). A new Monodontidae (Cetacea, Delphinoidea) from the lower Pliocene of Italy supports a warm-water origin for narwhals and white whales. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology, 39(3). {{doi|10.1080/02724634.2019.1645148}}</ref> \n\nThe fossil record also indicates that, in comparatively recent times, the beluga's range varied with that of the polar ice packs expanding during [[ice age]]s and contracting when the ice retreated.{{sfn|Perrin|Wursig|2009|p=214}} Counter-evidence to this theory{{clarify|date=February 2020}} comes from the finding in 1849 of fossilised beluga bones in [[Vermont]] in the United States, {{convert|240|km|abbr=on}} from the Atlantic Ocean. The bones were discovered during construction of the first railroad between [[Rutland (city), Vermont|Rutland]] and [[Burlington, Vermont|Burlington]] in Vermont, when workers unearthed the bones of a mysterious animal in [[Charlotte, Vermont|Charlotte]]. Buried nearly {{convert|10|ft|abbr=on}} below the surface in a thick blue [[clay]], these bones were unlike those of any animal previously discovered in Vermont. Experts identified the bones as those of a beluga. Because Charlotte is over {{convert|150|mi|abbr=on}} from the nearest ocean, early naturalists were at a loss to explain the presence of the bones of a [[marine mammal]] buried beneath the fields of rural Vermont.\n\nThe remains were found to be preserved in the sediments of the [[Champlain Sea]], an extension of the Atlantic Ocean within the continent resulting from the rise in sea level at the end of the ice ages some 12,000 years ago.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uvm.edu/whale/ |title=Charlotte, The Vermont Whale \u2013 An Electronic Museum |publisher=University of Vermont |accessdate=2 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219080758/http://www.uvm.edu/whale/ |archivedate=19 December 2010 }}</ref> Today, the [[Charlotte whale]] is the official Vermont State Fossil (making Vermont the only state whose official fossil is that of a still extant animal).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uvm.edu/whale/state_fossil.html |title=Our State Fossil |last=Wright |first=Wesley |publisher=University of Vermont |year=2009 |accessdate=23 August 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160810203554/http://www.uvm.edu/whale/state_fossil.html |archivedate=10 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Charlotte Whale.png|thumb|The cranium and mandible of the Charlotte whale (white) restored with the skull of a modern beluga whale (black)]]\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Beluga premier.gov.ru-3.jpeg|thumb|Front view of a beluga whale in captivity]]\nIts body is round, particularly when well fed, and tapers less smoothly to the head than the tail. The sudden tapering to the base of its neck gives it the appearance of shoulders, unique among cetaceans. The tailfin grows and becomes increasingly and ornately curved as the animal ages. The flippers are broad and short\u2014making them almost square-shaped.\n\n=== Longevity ===\nPreliminary investigations suggested a beluga's [[life expectancy]] was rarely more than 30 years.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Burns J.J. |author2=Seaman G.A. |title=Investigations of belukha whales in coastal waters of western and northern Alaska, 1982\u20131983: marking and tracking of whales in Bristol Bay |journal=Biology and Ecology. US Dept Commer, NOAA, OCSEAP Final Rep, II |volume=56 |year=1983 |pages=221\u2013357 |osti = 6361651}}</ref> The method used to calculate the age of a beluga is based on counting the layers of [[dentin]] and [[Cementum|dental cement]] in a specimen's teeth, which were originally thought to be deposited once or twice a year. The layers can be readily identified as one layer consists of opaque dense material and the other is transparent and less dense. It is therefore possible to estimate the age of the individual by extrapolating the number of layers identified and the estimated frequency with which the deposits are laid down.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Growth Layer Groups (GLGs) in the Teeth of an Adult Belukha Whale (''Delphinapterus leucas'') of Known Age: Evidence for Two Annual Layers |journal=Marine Mammal Science |volume=3 |year=1987 |pages=14\u201321 |doi=10.1111/j.1748-7692.1987.tb00148.x |issue=1 |last1=Goren |first1=Arthur D. |last2=Brodie |first2=Paul F. |last3=Spotte |first3=Stephen |last4=Ray |first4=G. Carleton |last5=Kaufman |first5=H. W. |last6=Gwinnett |first6=A. John |last7=Sciubba |first7=James J. |last8=Buck |first8=John D.}}</ref> A 2006 study using [[radiocarbon dating]] of the dentine layers showed the deposit of this material occurs with a lesser frequency (once per year) than was previously thought. The study therefore estimated belugas can live for 70 or 80 years.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://rparticle.web-p.cisti.nrc.ca/rparticle/AbstractTemplateServlet?calyLang=eng&journal=cjz&volume=84&year=2006&issue=12&msno=z06-182 |title=Bomb radiocarbon dating calibrates beluga (''Delphinapterus leucas'') age estimates |journal=Can. J. Zool. |volume=84 |year=2006 |pages=1840\u20131852 |doi=10.1139/Z06-182 |issue=12 |last1=Stewart |first1=R.E.A. |last2=Campana |first2=S.E. |last3=Jones |first3=C.M. |last4=Stewart |first4=B.E.}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Size ===\nThe species presents a moderate degree of [[sexual dimorphism]], as the males are 25% longer than the females and are sturdier.<ref name=cms /> Adult male belugas can range from {{convert|3.5|to|5.5|m|abbr=on}}, while the females measure {{convert|3|to|4.1|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name=princeton>{{cite book |title=Whales, Dolphins and Other Marine Mammals of the World |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=yyUXAQAAIAAJ |page=97}}|author1=Shirihai, H. |author2=Jarrett, B. |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2006|pages=97\u2013100|isbn=978-0-691-12757-6|publisher=Princeton Univ. Press|location=Princeton}}</ref> Males weigh between {{convert|1100|and|1600|kg|-1|abbr=on}}, and occasionally up to {{convert|1900|kg|-1|abbr=on}} while females weigh between {{convert|700|and|1200|kg|-1|abbr=on}}.<ref name=audubon>{{cite book |title=Guide to Marine Mammals of the World |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=5CYXAQAAIAAJ |page=318}}|author=Reeves, R. |author2=Stewart, B. |author3=Clapham, P. |author4=Powell, J. |last-author-amp=yes |pages=318\u2013321|year=2003|isbn=978-0-375-41141-0|publisher=A.A. Knopf|location=New York}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/species-especes/species-especes/belugaStLa-eng.htm Aquatic Species at Risk \u2013 Beluga Whale (St. Lawrence Estuary population)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211095606/http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/species-especes/species-especes/belugaStLa-eng.htm |date=11 December 2011 }}. Fisheries and Oceans Canada</ref> They rank as mid-sized species among toothed whales.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-336-01-0001.pdf |journal=Mammalian Species |title=''Delphinapterus leucas'' |volume=336 |issue=336 |pages=1\u20138 |vauthors=Stewart BE, Stewart RE |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1989 |doi=10.2307/3504210 |jstor=3504210 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615020035/http://www.science.smith.edu/msi/pdf/i0076-3519-336-01-0001.pdf |archivedate=15 June 2013 |access-date=22 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIndividuals of both sexes reach their maximum size by the time they are 10 years old.<ref name=ridgway>{{cite book |author1=Ridgway, S. |author2=Harrison, R. |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1981 |title=Handbook of Marine Mammals |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=At4jWmmaq6QC |page=486}}|edition=6|location= San Diego |publisher= Academic Press Limited|page=486|isbn=978-0-12-588506-5}}</ref> The beluga's body shape is stocky and fusiform (cone-shaped with the point facing backwards), and they frequently have folds of fat, particularly along the ventral surface.<ref name=seaworldphy>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bephysical.html |publisher=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Physical Characteristics |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619233020/http://seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bephysical.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Between 40% and 50% of their body weight is fat, which is a higher proportion than for cetaceans that do not inhabit the Arctic, where fat only represents 30% of body weight.<ref name=paine /><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Sergeant, D. E. |author2=Brodie, P. F. |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Body Size in White Whales, ''Delphinapterus leucas'' |journal=Journal Fisheries Research Board of Canada |volume=26 |year=1969 |pages=2561\u20132580 |issue=10 |doi=10.1139/f69-251}}</ref> The fat forms a layer that covers all of the body except the head, and it can be up to {{convert|15|cm|abbr=on}} thick. It acts as insulation in waters with temperatures between 0 and 18&nbsp;\u00b0C, as well as being an important reserve during periods without food.<ref>{{cite book |author=United Nations Environment Programme \u2013 Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals |title=Review of small cetaceans: distribution, behaviour, migration and threats: 177 (Marine mammal action plan/regional seas reports and studies) |year=2006 |publisher=UNEP/CMS |isbn=978-3-937429-02-1 |page=356}}</ref>\n\n=== Colour ===\n[[File:Delphinapterus leucas 2.jpg|thumb|left| Head of a beluga showing its distinctive white coloring and the large frontal prominence that houses the melon]]\n\nThe adult beluga is rarely mistaken for any other species, because it is completely white or whitish-grey in colour.<ref name=eol /> Calves are usually born grey,<ref name=princeton /> and by the time they are a month old, have turned dark grey or blue grey. They then start to progressively lose their pigmentation until they attain their distinctive white colouration, at the age of seven years in females and nine in males.<ref name=eol>{{cite web |url=http://www.eol.org/pages/328541?category_id=304 |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Life |title=''Delphinapterus leucas'' \u2013 Morphology, Physical Description |accessdate=3 August 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The white colouration of the skin is an adaptation to life in the Arctic that allows belugas to camouflage themselves in the polar ice caps as protection against their main predators, [[polar bear]]s and [[killer whales]].<ref name=friedman>{{cite journal |url=http://www.cogsci.ucsd.edu/~johnson/text/Friedman_BelugaOverview.pdf |author=Friedman W. R. |title=Environmental Adaptations of the Beluga Whale (''Delphinapterus leucas'') |journal=Cognitive Science |volume=143 |date=June 2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030131945/http://www.cogsci.ucsd.edu/~johnson/text/Friedman_BelugaOverview.pdf |archivedate=30 October 2012}}</ref> Unlike other cetaceans, the belugas seasonally [[Moulting|shed]] their skin.<ref name = moult /> During the winter, the [[Epidermis (skin)|epidermis]] thickens and the skin can become yellowish, mainly on the back and fins. When they migrate to the estuaries during the summer, they rub themselves on the gravel of the riverbeds to remove the cutaneous covering.<ref name=moult>{{cite journal |url=http://rparticle.web-p.cisti.nrc.ca/rparticle/AbstractTemplateServlet?calyLang=eng&journal=cjz&volume=68&year=1990&issue=2&msno=z90-051 |author=St. Aubin, D. J. |author2=Smith, T. G. |author3=Geraci, J. R. |title=Seasonal Epidermal Molt in Beluga Whales, ''Delphinapterus leucas'' |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |volume=68 |year=1990 |pages=339\u2013367 |doi=10.1139/z90-051 |issue=2}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n=== Head and neck ===\n[[File:Delphinapterus leucas head 1.jpg|thumb|[[Blowhole (anatomy)|Spiracle]] in the back of a beluga's head]]\n[[File:Delphinapterus leucas beluga MNHN.jpg|thumb|The skull]]\nLike most [[toothed whales]], it has a compartment found at the centre of the forehead that contains an organ used for echolocation called a [[melon (whale)|melon]], which contains fatty tissue.<ref name=haley>{{cite book |author=Haley, Delphine |title=Marine Mammals of Eastern North Pacific and Arctic Waters |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=y3QXAQAAIAAJ}}|edition=2|location= Seattle |publisher=Pacific Search Press|year= 1986 |isbn=978-0-931397-14-1}}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref> The shape of the beluga's head is unlike that of any other cetacean, as the melon is extremely bulbous, lobed and visible as a large frontal prominence.<ref name=haley /> Another distinctive characteristic it possesses is the melon is malleable; its shape is changed during the emission of sounds.<ref name=\"encyc\" /> The beluga is able to change the shape of its head by blowing air around its [[Paranasal sinuses|sinuses]] to focus the emitted sounds.<ref name=seaworldcom>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/becommunication.html |publisher=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Communication and Echolocation |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619233228/http://seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/becommunication.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Turl, C.W. |title=Echolocation abilities of the beluga, ''Delphinapterus leucas'': a review and comparison with the bottlenose dolphin, ''Tursiops truncatus'' |editor1=T.G. Smith |editor2=D.J. St. Aubin |editor3=J.R. Geraci. |journal=Can. Bull. Fish. Aquat. Sci |volume=224 |year=1990 |pages=119\u2013128}}</ref> This organ contains [[fatty acid]]s, mainly [[isovaleric acid]] (60.1%) and long-chain branched acids (16.9%), a very different composition from its body fat, and which could play a role in its echolocation system.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF02531529 |title=Isovaleroyl triglycerides from the blubber and melon oils of the beluga whale (''Delphinapterus leucas'') |year=1971 |last1=Litchfield |first1=Carter |last2=Ackman |first2=R. G. |last3=Sipos |first3=J. C. |last4=Eaton |first4=C. A. |journal=Lipids |volume=6 |issue=9 |pages=674\u201381 |pmid=5141491}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Squelette Delphinapterus leucas rdl.jpg|thumb|The skeleton]]\nUnlike many dolphins and whales, the seven [[vertebra]]e in the neck are not fused together, allowing the animal to turn its head laterally without needing to rotate its body.<ref name=\"Bonner, W.N. 17, 23\u201324\">{{cite book |author=Bonner, W.N. |title=Whales |url=https://archive.org/details/whales0000bonn/page/17 |publisher=Abe Books |location=Poole, England |isbn=978-0-7137-0887-5 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/whales0000bonn/page/17 17, 23\u201324] |year=1980 }}</ref> This gives the head a lateral manoeuvrability that allows an improved field of view and movement and helps in catching prey and evading predators in deep water.<ref name=friedman /> The [[rostrum (anatomy)|rostrum]] has about eight to ten small, blunt and slightly curved teeth on each side of the jaw and a total of 36 to 40 teeth.<ref name=nowak>{{cite book |author=Nowak, Ronald M. |title=Walker's Mammals of the World |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=89ybgDBCYKoC}}|volume= 2|edition=5|location= Baltimore|publisher= The Johns Hopkins University Press|year= 1991|isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8}}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref> Belugas do not use their teeth to chew, but for catching hold of their prey; they then tear them up and swallow them nearly whole.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fakr.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga.htm |author=The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's National Marine Fisheries Service \u2013 Alaska Regional Office |title=Beluga Whales |accessdate=3 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604062108/https://www.fakr.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga.htm |archivedate=4 June 2010|date=2 October 2018 }}</ref>\n\nBelugas only have a single [[Blowhole (anatomy)|spiracle]], which is located on the top of the head behind the melon, and has a muscular covering, allowing it to be completely sealed. Under normal conditions, the spiracle is closed and an animal must contract the muscular covering to open the spiracle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enchantedlearning.com/subjects/whales/anatomy/Blowhole.shtml |author=Enchanted Learning |title=Blowhole |accessdate=6 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100305073503/http://www.enchantedlearning.com/subjects/whales/anatomy/Blowhole.shtml |archivedate=5 March 2010}}</ref> A beluga's [[thyroid]] gland is larger than that of terrestrial [[mammal]]s\u2014weighing three times more than that of a horse\u2014which helps it to maintain a greater metabolism during the summer when it lives in river estuaries.<ref name=aubin /> It is the marine cetacean that most frequently develops [[Hyperplasia|hyperplastic]] and [[Neoplasia|neoplastic]] lesions of the thyroid.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1354/vp.40-6-698 |title=Adenomatous Hyperplasia of the Thyroid Gland in Beluga Whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') from the St. Lawrence Estuary and Hudson Bay, Quebec, Canada |year=2003 |last1=Mikaelian |first1=I. |last2=Labelle |first2=P. |last3=Kopal |first3=M. |last4=De Guise |first4=S. |last5=Martineau |first5=D. |journal=Veterinary Pathology |volume=40 |issue=6 |pages=698\u2013703 |pmid=14608025}}</ref>\n\n=== Fins ===\n[[File:Delphinapterus leucas in shallows.jpg|thumb|left|A beluga showing its tail fin in shallow water in [[Vancouver Aquarium]], Canada]]\nThe fins retain the bony vestiges of the beluga's mammalian ancestors, and are firmly bound together by [[connective tissue]].<ref name=seaworldphy /> The fins are small in relation to the size of the body, rounded and oar-shaped and slightly curled at the tips.<ref name=Leatherwood /> These versatile extremities are mainly used as a rudder to control direction, to work in synchrony with the tailfin and for agile movement in shallow waters up to {{convert|3|m|abbr=on}} deep.<ref name=ridgway /> The fins also contain a mechanism for [[thermoregulation|regulating body temperature]], as the [[Artery|arteries]] feeding the fin's muscles are surrounded by [[vein]]s that dilate or contract to gain or lose heat.<ref name=seaworldphy /><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Kasting NW, Adderley SA, Safford T, Hewlett KG |title=Thermoregulation in beluga (''Delphinapterus leucas'') and killer (''Orcinus orca'') whales |journal=Physiological Zoology |volume=62 |year=1989 |pages=687\u2013701 |jstor=30157921 |issue=3|doi=10.1086/physzool.62.3.30157921 }}</ref> The tailfin is flat with two oar-like lobes, it does not have any bones, and is made up of hard, dense, fibrous connective tissue. The tailfin has a distinctive curvature along the lower edge.<ref name=seaworldphy /> The longitudinal muscles of the back provide the ascending and descending movement of the tailfin, which has a similar thermoregulation mechanism to the pectoral fins.<ref name=seaworldphy />\n\nBelugas have a dorsal ridge, rather than a [[dorsal fin]].<ref name=princeton /> The absence of the dorsal fin is reflected in the genus name of the species\u2014''apterus'' the [[Greek language|Greek]] word for \"wingless\". The evolutionary preference for a dorsal ridge rather than a fin is believed to be an adaptation to under-ice conditions, or possibly as a way of preserving heat.<ref name=encyc /> The crest is hard and, along with the head, can be used to open holes in ice up to {{convert|8|cm|abbr=on}} thick.<ref name=belko>{{cite book |author1=Belkovitch, V. M. |author2=Shekotov, M. N. |title=The Belukha Whale: Natural Behavior and Bioacoustics |url=https://darchive.mblwhoilibrary.org/bitstream/handle/1912/75/Belukha%20Whale.pdf?sequence=1 |year=1993 |publisher=Woods Hole Oceanographic Inst. |location=Woods Hole, MA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407061734/https://darchive.mblwhoilibrary.org/bitstream/handle/1912/75/Belukha%20Whale.pdf?sequence=1 |archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Senses ===\n[[File:Toothed whale sound production.png|thumb|Emission and reception of sounds in a [[toothed whale]]]]\nThe beluga has a very specialised sense of hearing and its [[Cerebral cortex|auditory cortex]] is highly developed. It can hear sounds within the range of 1.2 to 120&nbsp;[[Hertz|kHz]], with the greatest sensitivity between 10 and 75&nbsp;kHz,<ref>{{cite book |author=Fay, R. R. |title=Hearing in Vertebrates: a Psychophysics Databook |journal=Acoustical Society of America Journal |volume=86 |issue=5 |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=DoJwQgAACAAJ |page=621}} |year=1988 |publisher=Hill-Fay Associates |location=Winnetka IL |isbn= 978-0-9618559-0-1|page=621 |bibcode=1989ASAJ...86.2044F |doi=10.1121/1.398550 }}</ref> where the average hearing range for humans is 0.02 to 20&nbsp;kHz.<ref>{{cite book |title=Music, Physics and Engineering |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=prLDAgAAQBAJ |page=249}} |author=Olson, Harry F |year= 1967|publisher=Dover Journals |isbn=978-0-486-21769-7 |page=249}}</ref> The majority of sounds are most probably received by the lower [[jaw]] and transmitted towards the [[middle ear]]. In the toothed whales, the lower jawbone is broad with a cavity at its base, which projects towards the place where it joins the [[cranium]]. A fatty deposit inside this small cavity connects to the middle ear.<ref name = senses /> Toothed whales also possess a small external auditory hole a few centimetres behind their eyes; each hole communicates with an external auditory conduit and an [[eardrum]]. It is not known if these organs are functional or simply [[Vestigial organ|vestigial]].<ref name=senses>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/besenses.html |author=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Senses |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619233050/http://seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/besenses.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBelugas are able to see within and outside of water, but their vision is relatively poor when compared to dolphins.<ref name=herman /> Their eyes are especially adapted to seeing under water, although when they come into contact with the air, the crystalline [[Lens (anatomy)|lens]] and the [[cornea]] adjust to overcome the associated [[myopia]] (the range of vision under water is short).<ref name=herman>{{cite book |author=Herman, Louis |title=Cetacean Behavior: Mechanisms and Functions |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=ShwXAQAAIAAJ |page=480}} |year=1988 |publisher=John Wiley and Sons |location=Nueva York |isbn=978-0-89464-272-2 |page=480}}</ref> A beluga's [[retina]] has [[Cone (cell)|cones]] and [[rod (cell)|rods]], which also suggests they can see in low light. The presence of cone cells indicates they can see colours, although this suggestion has not been confirmed.<ref name=herman /> Glands located in the medial corner of their eyes secrete an oily, gelatinous substance that lubricates the eye and helps flush out foreign bodies. This substance forms a film that protects the cornea and the [[conjunctiva]] from pathogenic organisms.<ref name=herman />\n\nStudies on captive animals show they seek frequent physical contact with other belugas.<ref name=friedman /> Areas in the mouth have been found that could act as [[chemoreceptor]]s for different tastes, and they can detect the presence of blood in water, which causes them to react immediately by displaying typical alarm behaviour.<ref name=friedman /> Like the other toothed whales, their brains lack [[olfactory bulb]]s and olfactory nerves, which suggests they do not have a sense of smell.<ref name=haley />\n\n== Behaviour ==\n=== Social structure and play ===\n\n[[File:Belugaschule 1999-07-02.jpg|thumb|Aerial view of a pod of belugas swimming at the surface]]\nThese cetaceans are highly sociable and they regularly form small groups, or pods, that may contain between two and 25 individuals, with an average of 10 members.<ref name=Katona>{{cite book |author=Katona, Steven K. |author2=Valerie Rough |author3=David T. Richardson |last-author-amp=yes |title=Field Guide to Whales, Porpoises, and Seals from Cape Cod to Newfoundland |edition=4 |year=1993 |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |isbn=978-1-56098-333-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/fieldguidetowhal00kato/page/336 336] |url=https://archive.org/details/fieldguidetowhal00kato/page/336 }}</ref> Pods tend to be unstable, meaning individuals tend to move from pod to pod. Radio tracking has even shown belugas can start out in one pod and within a few days be hundreds of miles away from that pod.<ref>{{cite book |year=2009 |title=Illustrated Encyclopedia of North American Mammals: A Comprehensive Guide to Mammals of North America |publisher=MobileReference |isbn=978-1-60501-279-7}}</ref> Beluga whale pods can be grouped into three categories, nurseries (which consist of mother and calves), bachelors (which consist of all males) and mixed groups. Mixed groups contain animals of both sexes.<ref>{{cite book |author=Slijper, E. J. |title=Whales |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=ywcXAQAAIAAJ |page=511}}|edition=2 |year=1979 |publisher=Cornell University Press |location=Ithaca, Nueva York |isbn=978-0-8014-1161-8 |page=511}}</ref> <ref name=nowak /> Many hundreds and even thousands of individuals can be present when the pods join together in river estuaries during the summer. This can represent a significant proportion of the total population and is when they are most vulnerable to being hunted.<ref>{{cite book |url=ftp://ftp.fao.org/docrep/fao/009/t0725e/t0725e00.pdf |vauthors=Jefferson TA, Leatherwood S, Webber MA |year=1993 |title=FAO Species identification guide. Marine mammals of the world |publisher=UNEP / FAO, Rome |page=320 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20130302192659/ftp://ftp.fao.org/docrep/fao/009/t0725e/t0725e00.pdf |archivedate=2 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThey are cooperative animals and frequently hunt in coordinated groups.<ref name=MacDonald /> The animals in a pod are very sociable and often chase each other as if they are playing or fighting, and they often rub against each other.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://rparticle.web-p.cisti.nrc.ca/rparticle/AbstractTemplateServlet?calyLang=eng&journal=cjz&volume=64&year=1986&issue=12&msno=z86-406 |author1=Sjare, Becky L. |author2=Thomas G. Smith |lastauthoramp=yes |title=The Relationship Between Behavioral Activity and Underwater Vocalizations of the White Whale, ''Delphinapterus leucas'' |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |volume=64 |year=1986 |pages=2824\u20132831 |doi=10.1139/z86-406 |issue=12}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Often individuals will surface and dive together in a synchronized manner, in a behavior known as milling.  \n\nIn captivity, they can be seen to be constantly playing, vocalising and swimming around each other.<ref name=behavior>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bebehavior.html |author=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Behavior |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619233419/http://seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bebehavior.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In one case, one whale blew bubbles, while the other one popped them. There have also been reports of beluga whales copying and imitating one another, similar to a game of Simon-says. Individuals have also been reported them displaying physical affection, via mouth to mouth contact.<ref>Yeater, D. B., Mill, H. M., & Noonan, M. (n.d.). What Do We Know about the Behavior of Belugas Studied from Managed Care .</ref> They also show a great deal of curiosity towards humans and frequently approach the windows in the tanks to observe them.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beluga Whale |author=Georgia Aquarium |url=http://www.georgiaaquarium.org/exploreTheAquarium/webcam-beluga.aspx |accessdate=12 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002175410/http://www.georgiaaquarium.org/exploreTheAquarium/webcam-beluga.aspx |archivedate=2 October 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nBelugas also show a great degree of curiosity towards humans in the wild, and frequently swim alongside boats.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.akhistorycourse.org/articles/article.php?artID=69 |author=Alaska Geographic Society |title=Alaska Whales and Whaling |location=Edmonds, Washington |publisher=Alaska Northwest Publishing Co |year=1979 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106031656/http://www.akhistorycourse.org/articles/article.php?artID=69 |archivedate=6 November 2012 |access-date=12 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> They also play with objects they find in the water; in the wild, they do this with wood, plants, dead fish and bubbles they have created.<ref name=paine /> During the breeding season, adults have been observed carrying objects such as plants, nets, and even the skeleton of a dead [[reindeer]] on their heads and backs.<ref name=behavior /> Captive females have also been observed displaying this behavior, carrying items such as floats and buoys, after they have lost a calf. Experts consider this interaction with the objects to be a substitute behavior.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://rparticle.web-p.cisti.nrc.ca/rparticle/AbstractTemplateServlet?calyLang=eng&journal=cjz&volume=64&year=1986&issue=7&msno=z86-237 |author1=Smith, T. G. |author2=Sleno, G. A. |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Do White Whales, ''Delphinapterus leucas'', Carry Surrogates in Response to Early Loss of Their Young |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |volume=64 |year=1986 |pages=1581\u20131582 |doi=10.1139/z86-237 |issue=7}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn captivity, mothering behavior among belugas depends on the individual. Some mothers are extremely attentive while other mothers are so blas\u00e9, that they have actually lost their calves. In aquaria, there have been cases where dominant females have stolen calves from mothers, particularly if they have lost a calf or if they are pregnant. After giving birth, dominant females will return the calf back to their mother. Additionally, male calves will temporarily leave their mothers to interact with an adult male who can serve as a role model for the calf, before they return to their mothers. Male calves are also frequently seen interacting with each other.<ref>Yeater, D. B., Mill, H. M., & Noonan, M. (n.d.). What Do We Know about the Behavior of Belugas Studied from Managed Care .</ref>\n\n=== Swimming and diving ===\nBelugas are slower swimmers than the other toothed whales, such as the killer whale and the [[common bottlenose dolphin]], because they are less hydrodynamic and have limited movement of their tailfins, which produce the greatest thrust.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=9739069 |year=1998 |last1=Fish |first1=FE |title=Comparative kinematics and hydrodynamics of odontocete cetaceans: Morphological and ecological correlates with swimming performance |volume=201 |issue=Pt 20 |pages=2867\u20132877 |journal=The Journal of Experimental Biology}}</ref> They frequently swim at speeds between {{convert|3|and|9|km/h|abbr=on}}, although they are able to maintain a speed of 22&nbsp;km/h for up to 15 min.<ref name=nowak /> Unlike most cetaceans, they are capable of swimming backwards.<ref name=ridgway /><ref>{{cite web |title=Georgia Aquarium \u2013 Beluga Whale |url=http://www.georgiaaquarium.org/exploreTheAquarium/webcam-beluga.aspx |accessdate=12 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081002175410/http://www.georgiaaquarium.org/exploreTheAquarium/webcam-beluga.aspx |archivedate=2 October 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Belugas swim on the surface between 5% and 10% of the time, while for the rest of the time they swim at a depth sufficient enough to cover their bodies.<ref name=ridgway /> They do not jump out of the water like dolphins or killer whales.<ref name=Leatherwood />\n\nThese animals usually only dive to depths to {{convert|20|m|abbr=on}},<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/beadaptations.html |author=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Adaptations for an Aquatic Environment |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619232933/http://seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/beadaptations.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> although they are capable of diving to greater depths. Individual captive animals have been recorded at depths between 400 and 647&nbsp;m below sea level,<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Sam H. |last1=Ridgway |first2=Donald A. |last2=Carder |first3=Tricia |last3=Kamolnick |first4=Robert R. |last4=Smith |first5=Carolyn E. |last5=Schlundt |first6=Wesley R. |last6=Elsberry |pmid=11807101 |year=2001 |title=Hearing and whistling in the deep sea: Depth influences whistle spectra but does not attenuate hearing by white whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') (Odontoceti, Cetacea) |volume=204 |issue=Pt 22 |pages=3829\u201341 |journal=The Journal of Experimental Biology}}</ref> while animals in the wild have been recorded as diving to a depth of more than 700&nbsp;m, with the greatest recorded depth being 872&nbsp;m.<ref name=deep>{{cite journal |first1=M. P. |last1=Heide-J\u00f8rgensen |first2=P. R. |last2=Richard |first3=A. |last3=Rosing-Asvid |date=March 1998 |title=Dive Patterns of Belugas (''Delphinapterus lencas'') in Waters near Eastern Devon Island |journal=Arctic |volume=51 |issue=1 |pages=17\u201326 |jstor=40511799 |doi=10.14430/arctic1041|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/ce2d9cfb6a453cb28dd4466f971703f5cbe8bed8 }}</ref> A dive normally lasts 3 to 5 minutes, but can last up to 18 minutes.<ref name=nowak /><ref name=deep /><ref name=MarineBioA>{{cite news |url=http://www.marinebio.org/species.asp?id=159 |title=''Delphinapterus leucas'': Beluga Whale |publisher=[[Marine Bio]] |accessdate=26 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410124651/http://marinebio.org/species.asp?id=159 |archivedate=10 April 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the shallower water of the estuaries, a diving session may last around two minutes; the sequence consists of five or six rapid, shallow dives followed by a deeper dive lasting up to one minute.<ref name=ridgway /> The average number of dives per day varies between 31 and 51.<ref name=deep />\n\nAll cetaceans, including belugas, have physiological adaptations designed to conserve oxygen while they are under water.<ref name=ridgway1972>{{cite book |author=Ridgway, Sam H |title=Mammals of the Sea. Biology and Medicine |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=7LdqAAAAMAAJ |page=812}} |year=1972 |publisher=Charles C. Thomas |location= Springfield, Illinois|isbn=978-0-398-02389-8 |page=812}}</ref> During a dive, these animals will reduce their heart rate from 100 beats a minute to between 12 and 20.<ref name=ridgway1972 /> Blood flow is diverted away from certain tissues and organs and towards the [[brain]], [[heart]] and [[lung]]s, which require a constant oxygen supply.<ref name=ridgway1972 /> The amount of oxygen dissolved in the blood is 5.5%, which is greater than that found in land-based mammals and is similar to that of [[Weddell seal]]s (a diving marine mammal). One study found a female beluga had 16.5 L of oxygen dissolved in her blood.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://rparticle.web-p.cisti.nrc.ca/rparticle/AbstractTemplateServlet?calyLang=eng&journal=cjz&volume=62&year=1984&issue=11&msno=z84-344 |author=Ridgway, S. H. |display-authors=etal |title=Diving and Blood Oxygen in the White Whale |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |volume=6 |year=1984 |pages=2349\u20132351 |doi=10.1139/z84-344 |issue=11 |last2=Bowers |last3=Miller |last4=Schultz |last5=Jacobs |last6=Dooley}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Lastly, the beluga's muscles contain high levels of the protein [[myoglobin]], which stores oxygen in muscle. Myoglobin concentrations in belugas are several times greater than for terrestrial mammals, which help prevent oxygen deficiency during dives.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S1095-6433(00)00182-3 |title=Body size and skeletal muscle myoglobin of cetaceans: Adaptations for maximizing dive duration |year=2000 |last1=Noren |first1=S.R. |last2=Williams |first2=T.M. |journal=Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology A |volume=126 |issue=2 |pages=181\u201391 |pmid=10936758}}</ref>\n\nBeluga whales often accompany [[bowhead whale]]s, for curiosity and to secure [[polynya]] feasibility to breathe as bowheads are capable of breaking through ice from underwater by headbutting.<ref>{{cite web |author=Dueck L. |year=2014 |title=3.2 Habits \u2013 3.2.1 Diving Characteristics and Sightability Estimates of Eastern Arctic Bowhead Whales Based on Satellite-Linked Telemetry |url=http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/science/coe-cde/cemam/report-rapport/sect3-eng.htm |publisher=The [[Fisheries and Oceans Canada]] |accessdate=30 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150130152825/http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/science/coe-cde/cemam/report-rapport/sect3-eng.htm |archivedate=30 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Diet ===\n[[File:Oncorhynchus keta.jpeg|thumb|[[Pacific salmon]], the staple diet of belugas from Alaska]]\nBelugas play an important role in the structure and function of marine resources in the [[Arctic Ocean]], as they are the most abundant toothed whales in the region.<ref name=Beaufort>{{cite journal |url=https://sites.google.com/site/soenixs/home/music/r-b |vauthors=Loseto LL, Stern GA, Connelly TL, Deibel D, Gemmill B, Prokopowicz A, Fortier L, Ferguson SH |title=Summer diet of beluga whales inferred by fatty acid analysis of the eastern Beaufort Sea food web |journal=J Exp Mar Biol Ecol |volume=374 |year=2009 |pages=12\u201318 |doi=10.1016/j.jembe.2009.03.015 |issue=1}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> They are opportunistic feeders; their feeding habits depend on their locations and the season.<ref name=cms>{{cite web |url=http://www.cms.int/reports/small_cetaceans/data/D_leucas/d_leucas.htm |author=Convention on Migratory Species \u2013 CMS |title=''Delphinapterus leucas'' (Pallas, 1776) |accessdate=3 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110821233643/http://www.cms.int/reports/small_cetaceans/data/D_leucas/d_leucas.htm |archivedate=21 August 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> For example, when they are in the [[Beaufort Sea]], they mainly eat [[Arctic cod]] (''Boreogadus saida'') and the stomachs of belugas caught near Greenland were found to contain [[rose fish]] (''Sebastes marinus''), [[Greenland halibut]] (''Reinhardtius hippoglossoides'') and [[northern shrimp]] (''Pandalus borealis''),<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Heide-Jorgensen, M.P. |author2=Teilmann, J |title=Growth, reproduction, age structure and feeding habits of white whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') in West Greenland waters |journal=Meddr Gronland, Biosci. |volume=39 |year=1994 |pages=195\u2013212}}</ref> while in Alaska their staple diet is [[Pacific salmon]] (''Oncorhynchus kisutch'').<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Frost, K.J. |author2=Lowry, L.F. |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Trophic importance of some marine gadids in Northern Alaska and their body-otolith size relationships |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285464411|journal=Fish. Bull. |volume=79 |year=1981 |pages=187\u2013192}}</ref> In general, the diets of these cetaceans consist mainly of fish; apart from those previously mentioned, other fish they feed on include [[capelin]] (''Mallotus villosus''), [[Smelt (fish)|smelt]], [[Sole (fish)|sole]], [[flounder]], [[herring]], [[sculpin]] and other types of [[salmon]].<ref name=lentifer /> They also consume a great quantity of invertebrates, such as [[shrimp]], [[squid]], [[crab]]s, [[clam]]s, [[octopus]], [[sea snail]]s, [[Polychaeta|bristle worms]] and other deep-sea species.<ref name=lentifer>{{cite book |author=Lentifer, J |title=Selected Marine Mammals of Alaska: Species Accounts with Research and Management Recommendations |publisher=Marine Mammals Commission |year=1988 |asin=B000102908}}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref><ref name=noaa2005>{{cite book |author=Perez, Michael A \u2013 NOAA |title=NOAA Technical Memorandum NMFS F/NWC-186. Review of Marine Mammal Population and Prey Information for Bering Sea Ecosystem Studies |publisher=NOAA |year=1990}}</ref> Belugas feed mainly in winter as their blubber is thickest in later winter and early spring, and thinnest in the fall. Inuit observation has led scientists to believe that belugas do not hunt during migration, at least in Hudson Bay <ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1139/cjz-2015-0259|title = Inuit Knowledge of beluga whale (Delphinapterus leucas) foraging ecology in Nunavik (Arctic Quebec), Canada|journal = Canadian Journal of Zoology|volume = 94|issue = 10|pages = 713\u2013726|year = 2016|last1 = Breton-Honeyman|first1 = K.|last2 = Hammill|first2 = M.O.|last3 = Furgal|first3 = C.M.|last4 = Hickie|first4 = B.|hdl = 1807/73843|hdl-access = free}}</ref> Animals in captivity eat 2.5% to 3.0% of their body weight per day, which equates to 18.2 to 27.2&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bediet.html |author=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Diet and Eating Habits |accessdate=30 July 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712115541/http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bediet.html |archivedate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Like their wild counterparts, captive belugas were found to eat less in the fall. <ref>{{cite journal |authors=Kastelein, R. A., Boxsel, M. van, Wiepkema, P. R., Ford, J., & Berghout, E. |year=1994 |title=Food consumption, growth and reproduction of Belugas (Delphinapterus leucas) in human care |url=https://www.aquaticmammalsjournal.org/share/AquaticMammalsIssueArchives/1994/Aquatic_Mammals_20_2/20.2Kastelein.pdf |journal=Aquatic Mammals |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=81\u201397}}</ref>\n\nForaging on the seabed typically takes place at depths between 20 and 40&nbsp;m,<ref>{{cite book |author=Katona, Steven K. |author2=Valerie Rough |author3=David T. Richardson. |last-author-amp=yes |title=A Field Guide to the Whales, Porpoises and Seals of the Gulf of Maine and Eastern Canada |url=https://archive.org/details/fieldguidetowhal0000kato/page/255 |year=1983 |publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons |location=New York |isbn=978-0-684-17902-5 |page=[https://archive.org/details/fieldguidetowhal0000kato/page/255 255] }}</ref> although they can dive to depths of 700&nbsp;m in search of food.<ref name=deep /><!-- repetitive A dive generally lasts between 3 and 5 minutes, but individuals have been observed to remain underwater for up to 18 minutes.<ref name=MarineBioB>{{cite web |url=http://www.marinebio.org/species.asp?id=159 |title=''Delphinapterus leucas'' |author=Beluga Whale \u2013 Marine Bio |accessdate=26 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://arctic.synergiesprairies.ca/arctic/index.php/arctic/article/viewFile/783/809 |vauthors=Richard PR, Martin AR, Orr JR |title=Summer and Autumn Movements of Belugas of the Eastern Beau-fort Sea Stock |journal=Arctic |year=2001 |pages=223\u2013236 |volume=54 |doi=10.14430/arctic783}}</ref> --> Their flexible necks provide a wide range of movement while they are searching for food on the ocean floor. Some animals have been observed to suck up water and then forcefully expel it to uncover their prey hidden in the silt on the seabed.<ref name=MacDonald>{{cite encyclopedia |last=MacDonald |first=David |encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of Mammals |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=XFgVnwEACAAJ |page=895}}|location= Nueva York| publisher= Facts on File, Inc. |year=1993 |page=895 |isbn=978-0-87196-871-5|title=The Encyclopedia of Mammals }}</ref> As their [[Tooth|teeth]] are neither large nor sharp, belugas must use suction to bring their prey into their mouths; it also means their prey has to be consumed whole, which in turn means it cannot be too large or the belugas run the risk of it getting stuck in their throats.<ref>{{cite book |oclc=18060784 |last=Lentifer |first=Jack W. |year=1988 |title=Selected Marine Mammals of Alaska: Species Accounts with Research and Management Recommendations |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Marine Mammals Commission |asin=B000102908}}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref> They also join together into coordinated groups of five or more to feed on [[Shoaling and schooling|shoals]] of fish by steering the fish into shallow water, where the belugas then attack them.<ref name=MacDonald /> For example, in the estuary of the [[Amur River]], where they mainly feed on salmon, groups of six or eight individuals join together to surround a shoal of fish and prevent their escape. Individuals then take turns feeding on the fish.<ref name=belko />\n\n=== Reproduction ===\n[[File:Delphinapterus leucas 16.jpg|thumb|Female and calf|alt=Underwater photo of calf swimming slightly below and behind its mother]]\nEstimations of the age of sexual maturity for beluga whales vary considerably; the majority of authors estimate males reach sexual maturity when they are between nine and fifteen years old, and females reach maturity when they are between eight and fourteen years old.<ref name=noaasex /> The average age at which females first give birth is 8.5 years and fertility begins to decrease when they are 25, eventually undergoing menopause,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ellis|first=Samuel|last2=Franks|first2=Daniel W.|last3=Nattrass|first3=Stuart|last4=Currie|first4=Thomas E.|last5=Cant|first5=Michael A.|last6=Giles|first6=Deborah|last7=Balcomb|first7=Kenneth C.|last8=Croft|first8=Darren P.|date=2018-08-27|title=Analyses of ovarian activity reveal repeated evolution of post-reproductive lifespans in toothed whales|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=8|issue=1|pages=12833|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-31047-8|pmid=30150784|pmc=6110730|issn=2045-2322|bibcode=2018NatSR...812833E}}</ref> and ceasing reproductive potential with no births recorded for females older than 41.<ref name=noaasex>{{cite web |url=http://www.fakr.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga/reproduction/suydam_dissertation2009.pdf |author=Suydam, Robert Scott |publisher=University of Washington |title=Age, growth, reproduction, and movements of beluga whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') from the eastern Chukchi Sea |year=2009 |accessdate=4 August 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919090346/http://www.fakr.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga/reproduction/suydam_dissertation2009.pdf |archivedate=19 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nFemale belugas typically give birth to one calf every three years.<ref name=princeton /> Most mating occurs usually February through May, but some mating occurs at other times of year.<ref name=encyc /> The beluga may have [[Embryonic diapause|delayed implantation]].<ref name=encyc /> Gestation has been estimated to last 12.0 to 14.5 months,<ref name=princeton /> but information derived from captive females suggests a longer gestation period up to 475 days (15.8 months).<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/zoo.20037 |title=Reproduction, Growth and Development in Captive Beluga (''Delphinapterus leucas'') |year=2005 |last1=Robeck |first1=Todd R. |last2=Monfort |first2=Steven L. |last3=Calle |first3=Paul P. |last4=Dunn |first4=J. Lawrence |last5=Jensen |first5=Eric |last6=Boehm |first6=Jeffrey R. |last7=Young |first7=Skip |last8=Clark |first8=Steven T. |journal=Zoo Biology |volume=24 |pages=29\u201349 |issue=1}}</ref> During the mating season, the testes mass of belugas will double in weight. Testosterone levels increase, but seems to be independent of copulation. Copulation typically takes place between 3 and 4 AM. <ref>Richard , J. T., Desfosses, R., Romano, T. A., & Sartini , B. L. (n.d.). Minimally Invasive Physiological Correlates of Intersexual Behavior in Belugas.</ref>\n\nCalves are born over a protracted period that varies by location. In the Canadian Arctic, calves are born between March and September, while in [[Hudson Bay]], the peak calving period is in late June, and in [[Cumberland Sound]], most calves are born from late July to early August.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Spring Sightings of Narwhal and Beluga Calves in Lancaster Sound, N.W.T |author1=Cosens, S. |author2=Dueck, L. |lastauthoramp=yes |date=June 1990 |pages=1\u20132 |journal=Arctic |volume=43 |issue=2 |doi=10.14430/arctic1602 |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic43-2-127.pdf |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028200611/http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic43-2-127.pdf |archivedate=28 October 2008}}</ref> Births usually take place in bays or estuaries where the water is warm with a temperature of 10 to 15&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref name=Katona /> Newborns are about {{convert|1.5|m|abbr=on}} long, weigh about {{convert|80|kg|abbr=on}}, and are grey in colour.<ref name=nowak /> They are able to swim alongside their mothers immediately after birth.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Delphinapterus_leucas.html |author=Animal Diversity Web \u2013 Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan |title=''Delphinapterus leucas'' |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606131422/http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/site/accounts/information/Delphinapterus_leucas.html |archivedate=6 June 2011}}</ref> The newborn calves nurse under water and initiate [[lactation]] a few hours after birth; thereafter, they feed at intervals around an hour.<ref name=MacDonald /> Studies of captive females have indicated their milk composition varies between individuals and with the stage of lactation; it has an average content of 28% fat, 11% protein, 60.3% water, and less than 1% residual solids.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bebirth.html |author=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Birth and Care of the Young |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619233106/http://seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bebirth.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The milk contains about 92 [[calories|cal]] per [[ounce]].<ref name=seaedu>{{cite book |author=Sea World Education Department |title=Toothed Whales |year=1993 |publisher=Sea World Education Department Publication |location=San Diego}}</ref>\n\nThe calves remain dependent on their mothers for nursing for the first year, when their teeth appear.<ref name=Katona /> After this, they start to supplement their diets with shrimp and small fish.<ref name=haley /> The majority of the calves continue nursing until they are 20 months old, although occasionally lactation can continue for more than two years,<ref name=nowak /> and lactational [[anoestrus]] may not occur. [[Alloparenting]] (care by females different from the mother) has been observed in captive belugas, including spontaneous and long-term milk production. This suggests this behaviour, which is also seen in other mammals, may be present in belugas in the wild.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/zoo.20295 |title=Allonursing in captive belugas (''Delphinapterus leucas'') |year=2010 |last1=Leung |first1=Elaine S. |last2=Vergara |first2=Valeria |last3=Barrett-Lennard |first3=Lance G. |journal=Zoo Biology |volume=29 |issue=5 |pages=633\u20137 |pmid=20127963}}</ref>\n\nHybrids have been documented between the beluga and the narwhal (specifically offspring conceived by a beluga father and a narwhal mother), as one, perhaps even as many as three, such hybrids were killed and harvested during a sustenance hunt. Whether or not these hybrids could breed remains unknown. The unusual dentition seen in the single remaining skull indicates the hybrid hunted on the seabed, much as walruses do, indicating feeding habits different from those of either parent species.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.livescience.com/65757-first-beluga-narwhal-hybrid.html | title=First-Ever Beluga-Narwhal Hybrid Found in the Arctic}}</ref><ref name=\"Skovrind2019\">{{cite journal|last1= Skovrind|first1= M.l|last2= Castruita|first2=J. A. S.|last3= Haile|first3= J.|last4= Treadaway|first4=E. C.|last5= Gopalakrishnan|first5= S.|last6= Westbury|first6=M. V.|last7= Heide-J\u00f8rgensen|first7=M. P.|last8= Szpak|first8= P.|last9= Lorenzen|first9=E. D.|title= Hybridization between two high Arctic cetaceans confirmed by genomic analysis|journal= Scientific Reports|volume= 9|issue= 1|pages= 7729|year= 2019|doi= 10.1038/s41598-019-44038-0|pmid= 31221994|pmc= 6586676|bibcode= 2019NatSR...9.7729S}}</ref>\n\n=== Communication and echolocation ===\n[[File:Beluga vocalizations.ogg|thumb|Vocalisations of ''Delphinapterus leucas'' published by [[NOAA]]]]\n\nBelugas use sounds and [[animal echolocation|echolocation]] for movement, communication, to find breathing holes in the ice, and to hunt in dark or turbid waters.<ref name=seaworldcom /> They produce a rapid sequence of clicks that pass through the melon, which acts as an acoustic lens to focus the sounds into a beam that is projected forward through the surrounding water.<ref name=seaedu /> These sounds spread through the water at a speed of nearly 1.6&nbsp;km per second, some four times faster than the speed of sound in air. The sound waves reflect from objects and return as echoes that are heard and interpreted by the animal.<ref name=seaworldcom /> This enables them to determine the distance, speed, size, shape and the object's internal structure within the beam of sound. They use this ability when moving around thick Arctic ice sheets, to find areas of unfrozen water for breathing, or air pockets trapped under the ice.<ref name=Katona />\n\nSome evidence indicates that belugas are highly sensitive to noise produced by humans. In one study, the maximum frequencies produced by an individual located in [[San Diego Bay]], [[California]], were between 40 and 60&nbsp;kHz. The same individual produced sounds with a maximum frequency of 100 to 120&nbsp;kHz when transferred to [[Kaneohe Bay]] in [[Hawaii]]. The difference in frequencies is thought to be a response to the difference in environmental noise in the two areas.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1121/1.392341 |pmid=3973242 |title=Demonstration of adaptation in beluga whale echolocation signals |journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America |volume=77 |issue=2 |pages=726\u201330 |year=1985 |last1=Au |first1=W. W. L. |last2=Carder |first2=D. A. |last3=Penner |first3=R. H. |last4=Scronce |first4=B. L. |bibcode=1985ASAJ...77..726A}}</ref>\n\nThese animals communicate using sounds of high frequency; their calls can sound like bird songs, so belugas were nicknamed \"canaries of the sea\".<ref>{{cite web |work=ePluribus Media |url=http://discuss.epluribusmedia.net/node/2903 |title=The Canaries of the Sea, granted a pardon, this time\u2026 |accessdate=7 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129143807/http://discuss.epluribusmedia.net/node/2903 |archivedate=29 November 2009}}</ref> Like the other toothed whales, belugas do not possess [[Vocal folds|vocal cords]] and the sounds are probably produced by the movement of air between the nasal sacks, which are located near to the blowhole.<ref name=seaworldcom />\n\nAs a, toothed whale, beluga calls can be broken down into the categories of whistles, clicks and burst calls. Whistles tend to indicate social communication while clicks indicate navigation and foraging. Burst calls tend to indicate aggression. <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Madsen | first1 = P. T. | last2 = Jensen | first2 = F. H. | last3 = Carder | first3 = D. | last4 = Ridgway | first4 = S. | year = 2011 | title = Dolphin whistles: a functional misnomer revealed by heliox breathing | url = | journal = Biology Letters | volume = 8 | issue = 2| pages = 211\u2013213 | doi = 10.1098/rsbl.2011.0701 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nBelugas are among the most vocal cetaceans.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/whalesofworld0000bonn/page/191 |url-status=dead |author=Bonner, W |year=1989 |title=Whales of the World |location=New York |publisher=Facts on File Journals |page=[https://archive.org/details/whalesofworld0000bonn/page/191 191] |isbn=978-0-8160-5216-5 }}</ref> They use their vocalisations for echolocation, during mating and for communication. They possess a large repertoire, emitting up to 11 different sounds, such as cackles, whistles, trills and squawks.<ref name=seaworldcom /> They make sounds by grinding their teeth or splashing, but they rarely use body language to make visual displays with their pectoral fins or tailfins, nor do they perform somersaults or jumps in the way other species do, such as dolphins.<ref name=seaworldcom /><!-- repetitive in a study by [[Japan]]ese researchers, belugas were able to identify three different objects using specific sounds for each one, suggesting humans may be able to communicate in some way with these marine mammals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.meeja.com.au/index.php?display_article_id=221 |title=Japanese whale whisperer teaches beluga to talk |publisher=meeja.com.au |accessdate=16 September 2008}}</ref>-->\n\nThere is heavy debate as to whether cetacean vocalizations can constitute a language. A study conducted in 2015 determined that European beluga signals share physical features comparable to \u201cvowels.\u201d These sounds were found to be stable throughout time, but varied among different geographical locations. The further away the populations were from each other, the more varied the sounds were in relation to one another. <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Panova | first1 = E. M. | last2 = Belikov | first2 = R. A. | last3 = Agafonov | first3 = A. V. | last4 = Kirillova | first4 = O. I. | last5 = Chernetsky | first5 = A. D. | last6 = Belkovich | first6 = V. M. | year = 2015 | title = Intraspecific variability in the \"vowel\"-like sounds of beluga whales (Delphinapterus leucas): Intra- and interpopulation comparisons | url = | journal = Marine Mammal Science | volume = 32 | issue = 2| pages = 452\u2013465 | doi = 10.1111/mms.12266 }}</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\n[[File:Territorio Beluga.png|thumb|Circumpolar distribution of beluga populations showing the main subpopulations]]\nThe beluga inhabits a discontinuous circumpolar distribution in Arctic and sub-Arctic waters.<ref name=rice>{{cite book |author=Rice DW |title=Marine mammals of the world: systematics and distribution |editor=Wartzok D |edition=4 |year=1998 |publisher=Society for Marine Mammalogy, Special Journal |location=Lawrence, KS. USA |isbn=978-1-891276-03-3 |page=231}}</ref> During the summer, they can mainly be found in deep waters ranging from [[76th parallel north|76\u00b0N]] to [[80th parallel north|80\u00b0N]], particularly along the coasts of [[Alaska]], northern [[Canada]], western [[Greenland]] and northern [[Russia]].<ref name=rice /> The southernmost extent of their range includes isolated populations in the [[St. Lawrence River]] in the Atlantic,<ref name=\"Canada DFO\">Fisheries and Oceans Canada. [http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/fm-gp/mammals-mammiferes/species-especes/beluga-eng.html Beluga Whale] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805184514/http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/fm-gp/mammals-mammiferes/species-especes/beluga-eng.html |date=5 August 2017 }}</ref> and the [[Amur River]] delta, the [[Shantar Islands]] and the waters surrounding [[Sakhalin Island]] in the [[Sea of Okhotsk]].<ref name=\"Burkanov\">{{cite book |last1=Artyukhin |first1=Yu.B. |last2=Burkanov |first2=V.N. |year=1999 |title=Sea birds and mammals of the Russian Far East: a Field Guide |location=Moscow |publisher=\u0410S\u0422 Publishing |p=215 |isbn=978-5237044751|language=ru}}</ref>\n\n=== Migration ===\n[[File:The Canadian field-naturalist (1980) (20332437900).jpg|thumb|Young Beluga seen in [[Great South Bay]], [[Long Island]], March\u2013July 1979]]\nBelugas have a seasonal [[Animal migration|migratory]] pattern.<ref name=suydam /> Migration patterns are passed from parents to offspring. Some travel as far as 6,000 kilometres per year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.zmescience.com/ecology/animals-ecology/whales-family-ties-06042018 |title=Beluga whales value culture and family ties |last=Andrei |first=Mihai |date=6 April 2018 |work=ZME Science |access-date=14 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180415125217/https://www.zmescience.com/ecology/animals-ecology/whales-family-ties-06042018/ |archive-date=15 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> When the summer sites become blocked with ice during the autumn, they move to spend the winter in the open sea alongside the pack ice or in areas covered with ice, surviving by using [[polynya]]s to surface and breathe.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://arctic.synergiesprairies.ca/arctic/index.php/arctic/article/view/790/0 |vauthors=Barber DG, Saczuk E, Richard PR |title=Examination of Beluga-Habitat Relationships through the Use of Telemetry and a Geographic Information System |journal=Arctic |volume=54 |year=2001 |pages=305\u2013316 |issue=3 |doi=10.14430/arctic790 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202143257/http://arctic.synergiesprairies.ca/arctic/index.php/arctic/article/view/790/0 |archivedate=2 February 2015}}</ref> In [[summer]] after the sheet ice has melted, they move to coastal areas with shallower water (1\u20133&nbsp;m deep), although sometimes they migrate towards deeper waters (>800 m).<ref name=suydam>{{cite journal |url=http://arctic.synergiesprairies.ca/arctic/index.php/arctic/article/view/784/0 |vauthors=Suydam RS, Lowry LF, Frost KJ, O' Corry-Crowe GM, Pikok D JR |title=Satellite Tracking of Eastern Chukchi Sea Beluga Whales into the Arctic Ocean |journal=Arctic |volume=54 |year=2001 |pages=237\u2013243 |issue=3 |doi=10.14430/arctic784 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202143250/http://arctic.synergiesprairies.ca/arctic/index.php/arctic/article/view/784/0 |archivedate=2 February 2015}}</ref> In the summer, they occupy [[estuary|estuaries]] and the waters of the [[continental shelf]], and, on occasion, they even swim up the rivers.<ref name=suydam /> A number of incidents have been reported where groups or individuals have been found hundreds or even thousands of kilometres from the ocean.<ref>{{cite news |title=Whale Carcass in Alaska River Mystifies Experts |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jun/16/nation/na-carcass16 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=16 June 2006 |accessdate=3 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111055050/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/jun/16/nation/na-carcass16 |archivedate=11 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Gewalt W |title=Handbuch der S\u00e4ugetiere Europas. Meeress\u00e4uger. Teil IA |language=German |year=1994 |publisher=Aula-Verlag, Wies-baden |isbn=978-3-89104-560-2 |chapter=Wale und Delphine 1 -''Delphinapterus leucas'' \u2013 Wei\u00dfwal oder Beluga |pages=185\u2013208}}</ref> One such example comes from June 9, 2006, when a young beluga carcass was found in the [[Tanana River]] near [[Fairbanks, Alaska|Fairbanks]] in central Alaska, nearly {{convert|1700|km|abbr=on}} from the nearest ocean habitat. Belugas sometimes follow migrating fish, leading Alaska state biologist Tom Seaton to speculate it had followed migrating [[salmon]] up the river at some point in the previous autumn.<ref>{{cite news |title=Beluga's body in river baffles scientists |url=http://articles.southbendtribune.com/2006-07-06/news/26933745_1_beluga-whale-carcass-scientists |work=South Bend Tribune |accessdate=10 September 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213002249/http://articles.southbendtribune.com/2006-07-06/news/26933745_1_beluga-whale-carcass-scientists |archivedate=13 December 2013}}</ref> The rivers they most often travel up include: the [[Northern Dvina River|Northern Dvina]], the [[Mezen River|Mezen]], the [[Pechora River|Pechora]], the [[Ob River|Ob]] and the [[Yenisei River|Yenisei]] in [[Asia]]; the [[Yukon River|Yukon]] and the [[Kuskokwim River|Kuskokwim]] in Alaska, and the Saint Lawrence in Canada.<ref name=rice /> Spending time in a river has been shown to stimulate an animal's metabolism and facilitates the seasonal renewal of the epidermal layer.<ref name=aubin>{{cite journal |author=Aubin DJST |title=Thyroid function and epidermal growth in beluga whales, ''Delphinapterus leucas'' |journal=Diss Abst Int Pt B Sci and Eng |volume=50 |year=1989 |issue=1}}</ref> In addition, the rivers represent a safe haven for newborn calves where they will not be preyed upon by killer whales.<ref name=encyc /> Calves often return to the same estuary as their mother in the summer, meeting her sometimes even after becoming fully mature.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alaskannature.com/beluga.htm |publisher=Alaskan Naure |title=Beluga Whale |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602192729/http://www.alaskannature.com/beluga.htm |archivedate=2 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe migration season is relatively predictable, as it is basically determined by the amount of daylight and not by other variable physical or biological factors, such as the condition of the sea ice.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Heide J\u00f8rgensen MP |author2=Reeves RR |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Evidence of a decline in beluga, ''Delphinapterus leucas'', abundance off West Greenland |journal=ICES J Mar Sci |volume=53 |issue=1 |year=1996 |pages=61\u201372 |doi=10.1006/jmsc.1996.0006|doi-access=free }}</ref> Vagrants may travel further south to areas such as [[Ireland|Irish]]<ref>Irish Whale and Dolphin Group. [http://www.iwdg.ie/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&id=2211:beluga-whale beluga whale] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308022553/http://iwdg.ie/index.php?id=2211:beluga-whale&option=com_k2&view=item |date=8 March 2016 }}. Retrieved 2 June 2014</ref> and [[Scotland|Scottish]] waters,<ref>[[BBC]] News. (21 February 2012) [https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-17100499 Beluga whale sightings in SNH marine renewables report] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602200353/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-17100499 |date=2 June 2014 }}. Retrieved 2 June 2014</ref> the islands of [[Orkney Islands|Orkney]]<ref>Wildlife Extra. [http://www.wildlifeextra.com/go/whales/scotland/#cr Dolphin and whale watching in the Scotland] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602213317/http://www.wildlifeextra.com/go/whales/scotland/ |date=2 June 2014 }}. Retrieved 2 June 2014</ref> and [[Hebrides]],<ref>Hebridean Whale and Dolphin Trust. [http://www.whaledolphintrust.com/species_details.asp?inst=19&species_id=139 Beluga Whale] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130620090221/http://www.whaledolphintrust.com/species_details.asp?inst=19&species_id=139 |date=20 June 2013 }}. Retrieved 2 June 2014</ref> and to [[Hokkaido|Japanese]] waters.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sato |first1=H. |last2=Ichimura |first2=M. |year=2011 |title=The Sighting Record of Beluga (White Whale) ''Delphinapterus leucas'' in Shiretoko\u2013Nemuro Strait Water, Eastern Hokkaido, Japan. Sea Life Watch in Shibetsu |journal=Bulletin of the Shiretoko Museum |volume=32 |pages=45\u201352}}</ref> There had been several vagrant individuals<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Uni |first1=Y |year=2006 |title=Whales, Dolphins and Porpoises off Shiretoko |url=http://www.cho.co.jp/natural-h/download/archive/shiretoko/2703s_UNI.pdf |journal=Bulletin of the Shiretoko Museum |volume=27 |pages=37\u201346 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714110246/http://www.cho.co.jp/natural-h/download/archive/shiretoko/2703s_UNI.pdf |archivedate=14 July 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> that have demonstrated seasonal residencies at [[Muroran|Volcano Bay]],<ref>[http://www.bekkoame.ne.jp/~tnfuruya/vmwa/ Volcano-bay Marine-animals Waching Association] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923183609/http://www.bekkoame.ne.jp/~tnfuruya/vmwa/ |date=23 September 2015 }} of Muroran Renaissance</ref><ref>Mukai. T., [http://www.kk-elm.jp/ KK-ELM] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151020131946/http://kk-elm.jp/ |date=20 October 2015 }}. Retrieved 2 June 2014</ref><ref>Sasamori K., [http://www.muro-nc.com/watching/animals.htm Muroran Dolphin and Whale Watching] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714161348/http://www.muro-nc.com/watching/animals.htm |date=14 July 2014 }}. Retrieved 2 June 2014</ref> and a unique whale were used to return annually to areas adjacent to [[Shibetsu]] in [[Nemuro Strait]] in the 2000s.<ref>Imai Y., [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLAILdeR3ZgA6yKDAbnv6wg2v0IefgSKTj \u91ce\u751f\u306e\u30b7\u30ed\u30a4\u30eb\u30ab/\u30d9\u30eb\u30fc\u30ac in \u65e5\u672c Beluga, the White Whale observations in Japanese waters.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608103137/https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLAILdeR3ZgA6yKDAbnv6wg2v0IefgSKTj |date=8 June 2015 }}. [[YouTube]]. Retrieved 2 June 2014</ref> On rarer occasions, individuals of vagrancy can reach the [[Korean Peninsula]].<ref>[http://www.whalelove.com/whale2_02.html \ud770\uace0\ub798  Delphinaterus leucas     \uc601\uba85 : Beluga, White whale \uc77c\uba85 : \uc2dc\ub85c\uc774\ub8e8\uce74] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074416/http://www.whalelove.com/whale2_02.html |date=4 March 2016 }}. whalelove.com</ref> A few other individuals have been confirmed to return to the coasts of Hokkaido, and one particular individual became a resident in [[brackish water]]s of [[Lake Notoro]] since in 2014.<ref>[http://9765145552aa0409.lolipop.jp/wp-content/uploads/pdf/umihirumo149.pdf \u30d9\u30eb\u30fc\u30ac\uff08\u30b7\u30ed\u30a4\u30eb\u30ab\uff09 ''Delphinapterus leucas''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120112425/http://9765145552aa0409.lolipop.jp/wp-content/uploads/pdf/umihirumo149.pdf |date=20 November 2015 }}. Association for Protection of Marine Communities (1 January 2015)</ref><ref>Nakayama Y.. 2016. [http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASJ7C6X5FJ7CUTIL06R.html \u5317\u6975\u306e\u30d9\u30eb\u30fc\u30ac\u3001\u5317\u6d77\u9053\u3067\u3072\u3068\u308a\u307c\u3063\u3061\u3000\u904a\u3073\u76f8\u624b\u306f\u6f01\u5e2b] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325025656/http://www.asahi.com/articles/ASJ7C6X5FJ7CUTIL06R.html |date=25 March 2017 }}. The [[Asahi Shimbun]]. Retrieved 25 March 2017</ref>\n\nSome populations are not migratory and certain resident groups will stay in well-defined areas, such as in [[Cook Inlet]], the estuary of the Saint Lawrence River and Cumberland Sound.<ref name=reyes /> The population in Cook Inlet stays in the waters furthest inside the inlet during the summer until the end of autumn. Then during the winter, they disperse to the deeper water in the center of the inlet, but without completely leaving it.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://staff.washington.edu/klaidre/docs/Hobbsetal_2005.pdf |vauthors=Hobbs RC, Laidre KL, Vos DJ, Mahoney BA, Eagleton M |title=Movements and Area Use of Belugas, ''Delphinapterus leucas'', in a Subarctic Alaskan Estuary |journal=Arctic |volume=58 |issue=4 |year=2005 |pages=331\u2013340 |doi=10.14430/arctic447 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210101842/http://staff.washington.edu/klaidre/docs/Hobbsetal_2005.pdf |archivedate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afsc.noaa.gov/Journals/AFSC-TM/NOAA-TM-AFSC-145.pdf |vauthors=Rugh DJ, Mahoney BA, Smith BK |work=NOAA Technical Memorandum NMFS AFSC. no. 145 |title=Aerial Surveys of Beluga Whales in Cook Inlet, Alaska, Between June 2001 and June 2002 |year=2004 |page=20 |accessdate=7 August 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn April, the animals that spend the winter in the center and southwest of the [[Bering Sea]] move to the north coast of Alaska and the east coast of Russia.<ref name=reyes /> The populations living in the [[Ungava Bay]] and the eastern and western sides of [[Hudson Bay]] overwinter together beneath the sea ice in [[Hudson Strait]]. Whales in [[James Bay]] that spend winter months within the basin, could be a distinct group from those in Hudson Bay.<ref>[http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/csas-sccs/Publications/ResDocs-DocRech/2012/2012_074-eng.html Beluga whales in James Bay: a separate entity from eastern Hudson Bay belugas?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024221222/http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/csas-sccs/Publications/ResDocs-DocRech/2012/2012_074-eng.html |date=24 October 2016 }}</ref> The populations of the [[White Sea]], the [[Kara Sea]] and the [[Laptev Sea]] overwinter in the Barents Sea.<ref name=reyes /> In the spring, the groups separate and migrate to their respective summer sites.<ref name=reyes />\n\n=== Habitat ===\n[[File:Beluga 1 1999-07-03.jpg|thumb|Beluga in the mouth of the [[Churchill River (Hudson Bay)|Churchill River]] in the [[Hudson Bay]], Canada]]\nBelugas exploit a varied range of habitats; they are most commonly seen in shallow waters close to the coast, but they have also been reported to live for extended periods in deeper water, where they feed and give birth to their young.<ref name=reyes>{{cite book |author=Reyes JC |year=1991 |title=The conservation of small cetaceans: a review. Report prepared for the Secretariat of the Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals |publisher=UNEP/CMS Secretariat, Bonn}}</ref>\n\nIn coastal areas, they can be found in [[cove]]s, [[fjord]]s, [[canal]]s, [[bay]]s and shallow waters in the Arctic Ocean that are continuously lit by sunlight.<ref name=paine /> They are also often seen during the summer in river estuaries, where they feed, socialize and give birth to young. These waters usually have a temperature between 8 and 10&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref name=paine>{{cite book |author=Paine, S. |year=1995 |title=The World of the Arctic Whales |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=ULOlOwAACAAJ}} |publisher= San Francisco: Sierra Club |isbn=978-0-87156-957-8}}</ref> The [[mudflat]]s of Cook Inlet in Alaska are a popular location for these animals to spend the first few months of summer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alaskafisheries.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga/reports/habitatuse012507.pdf |title=Habitat use in a marine ecosystem: beluga whales ''Delphinapterus leucas'' in Cook Inlet, Alaska |author1=Goetz, Kimberly T. |author2=Rugh, David J. |author3=Read, Andrew J. |author4=Hobbs, Roderick C. |lastauthoramp=yes |work=National Marine Mammal Laboratory, Alaska Fisheries Science Center, NMFS, NOAA, Washington, USA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615034512/https://alaskafisheries.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga/reports/habitatuse012507.pdf |archivedate=15 June 2010|date=2 October 2018  }}</ref> In the eastern Beaufort Sea, female belugas with their young and immature males prefer the open waters close to land, while the adult males live in waters covered by ice near the [[Canadian Arctic Archipelago]]. The younger males and females with slightly older young can be found nearer to the ice shelf.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://rparticle.web-p.cisti.nrc.ca/rparticle/AbstractTemplateServlet?calyLang=eng&journal=cjz&volume=84&year=&issue=12&msno=z06-160 |title=Segregation of Beaufort Sea beluga whales during the open-water season |author1=Loseto, L.L. |author2=Richard, P. |author3=''Stern'', G.A. |author4=Orr, J. |author5=Ferguson, S.H. |journal=Canadian Journal of Zoology |volume=84 |date=1 December 2006 |pages=1743\u20131751(9) |doi=10.1139/Z06-160 |issue=12}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Generally, the use of different habitats in summer reflects differences in feeding habits, risk from predators and reproductive factors for each of the subpopulations.<ref name=cms />\n\n== Population ==\nThere are currently 22 stocks of beluga whales recognized: <ref>NAMMCO (2018) Report of the NAMMCO Global Review of Monodontids. 13-16 March 2017, Hiller\u00f8d, Denmark, Available at https://nammco.no/topics/sc-working-group-reports/ </ref>\n\n1.\tJames Bay- 14,500 individuals (belugas remain here all year round)\n2.\tWestern Hudson Bay- 55,000 individuals \n3.\tEastern Hudson Bay- 3,400-3,800 individuals \n4.\tCumberland Sound- 1,151 individuals \n5.\tUngava Bay- 32 individuals (maybe functionally extinct)\n6.\tSt. Lawrence River Estuary- 889 individuals \n7.\tEastern Canadian Arctic- 21,400 individuals \n8.\tSouthwest Greenland- Extinct\n9.\tEastern Chukchi Sea- 20,700 individuals \n10.\tEastern Bering Sea- 7,000-9,200 individuals \n11.\tEastern Beaufort Sea- 39,300 individuals \n12.\tBristol Bay- 2,000-3,000 individuals \n13.\tCook Inlet- 300 individuals \n14.\tWhite Sea- 5,600 individuals\n15.\tKara Sea/Laptev Sea/Barents Sea- Data Deficient\n16.\tUlbansky- 2,300\n17.\tAnadyr- 3,000\n18.\tShelikhov- 2,666\n19.\tSakhalin/Amur- 4,000 individuals \n20.\tTugursky- 1,500 individuals \n21.\tUdskaya- 2,500 individuals \n22.\tSvalbard- 529 individuals \n\n\n\nThe Yakatat Bay belugas are not considered to be a true stock because they have only been present in these waters since the 1980s, and are believed to be of Cook Inlet origin. It is estimated that less than 20 whales inhabit the bay year-round. Overall the beluga population is estimated to be between 150,000-200,000 animals.\n\n== Threats ==\n\n=== Hunting ===\n[[File:Belugas+Narwhals.png|thumb|Beluga and narwhal catches]]\n[[File:Beluga caza.jpg|thumb|Illustration from 1883 showing [[Dena'ina]] hunting party harpooning a beluga in [[Cook Inlet]], [[Alaska]]]]\nThe native populations of the Arctic in Alaska, Canada, Greenland and Russia hunt belugas, for both consumption and profit. Belugas have been easy prey for hunters due to their predictable migration patterns and the high population density in estuaries and surrounding coastal areas during the summer.<ref name=ellis />\n\n==== Present ====\nThe number of animals killed is about 1,000 per year, with 300 to 400 killed in Alaska, another 300 to 400 in Canada, and fewer in Greenland and Russia (see table below. and its sources). Questions remain whether the number of whales killed is sustainable.<ref name=dold>{{cite journal |url=http://www.faqs.org/abstracts/Zoology-and-wildlife-conservation/The-great-white-whales-Trees-make-a-great-target.html |author=Dold, Catherine |title=The Great White Whales |journal=Wildlife Conservation |date=July\u2013August 1993 |pages=45\u201353 |issn=1048-4949}}</ref> Beluga whale hunting quotas in Canada and the United States are established using the Potential Biological Removal equation PBR = Nmin * 0.5 * Rmax * FR, to determine what constitutes a sustainable hunt. Nmin represents a conservative estimation of the population size, Rmax, represents the maximum rate of population increase and FR represents the recovery factor. <ref>NAMMCO (2018) Report of the NAMMCO Global Review of Monodontids. 13-16 March 2017, Hiller\u00f8d, Denmark, Available at https://nammco.no/topics/sc-working-group-reports</ref>\n\nHunters in Hudson's Bay rarely eat the meat. They give a little to dogs, and leave the rest for wild animals.<ref name=\"hoover\" /> Other areas may dry the meat for later consumption by humans. In Greenland the skin ([[muktuk]]) is sold commercially to fish factories,<ref name=\"heide1994\">{{Cite journal |last=Heide-J\u00f8rgensen |first=Mads Peter |date=January 1994 |title=Distribution, exploitation and population status of white whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') and narwhals (''Monodon monoceros'') in West Greenland |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/285286297 |journal=Meddelelser om Gr\u00f8nland, Bioscience |volume=39 |pages=135\u2013149}}</ref> and in Canada to other communities.<ref name=\"hoover\" /> An average of one or two vertebrae and one or two teeth per beluga are carved and sold.<ref name=\"hoover\" /> One estimate of the annual gross value received from Beluga hunts in [[Hudson Bay]] in 2013 was {{CAD|600,000}} for 190 belugas, or {{CAD|3,000}} per beluga. However, the net income, after subtracting costs in time and equipment, was a loss of {{CAD|60}} per person. Hunts receive subsidies, but they continue as a tradition, rather than for the money, and the economic analysis noted that whale watching may be an alternate revenue source. Of the gross income, {{CAD|550,000}} was for skin and meat, to replace beef, pork and chickens which would otherwise be bought. {{CAD|50,000}} was received for carved vertebrae and teeth.<ref name=\"hoover\">{{Cite journal |vauthors=Hoover C, Bailey M, Higdon J, Ferguson SH, Sumalia R |date=March 2013 |title=Estimating the Economic Value of Narwhal and Beluga Hunts in Hudson Bay, Nunavut |journal= Arctic|volume=66 |pages=1\u201316 |doi=10.14430/arctic4261|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/60939002dc02bbf9f96e4da3d0a4c7d1a98a11eb }}</ref>\n\nRussia now harvests 5 to 30 belugas per year for meat and captures an additional 20 to 30 per year for live export to Chinese [[aquarium|aquaria]].<ref name=\"bettridge\" /><ref name=\"master\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-marineparks-insight/tidal-wave-of-chinese-marine-parks-fuels-murky-cetacean-trade-idUSKCN1M00OC |title=Tidal wave of Chinese marine parks fuels murky cetacean trade |last=Master |first=Farah |date=2018-09-20 |work=Reuters |access-date=2018-11-17 }}</ref> However, in 2018, 100 were illegally captured for live export.<ref name=\"kustikova\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2018/11/09/78512-eto-kak-sizo |title=It's like a detention center!, \"\u042d\u0442\u043e \u043a\u0430\u043a \u0421\u0418\u0417\u041e!\" |last=Kustikova |first=Alisa |date=2018-11-08 |work=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u2013 Novayagazeta.ru |access-date=2018-11-23 |language=ru-RU}}</ref><ref name=\"prim\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/news/2018/11/23/147025-v-primorie-sud-nalozhil-arest-na-kosatok-i-beluh-v-buhte-pod-nahodkoy |title=In Primorye, the court arrested killer whales and belugas in the case of the illegal export of mammals abroad, \u0412 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0435 \u0441\u0443\u0434 \u0430\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u043a\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043a \u0438 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u0443\u0445 \u043f\u043e \u0434\u0435\u043b\u0443 \u043e \u043d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043d\u043e\u043c \u0432\u044b\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0435 \u043c\u043b\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u0437\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0443 |date=2018-11-23 |work=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u2013 Novayagazeta.ru |access-date=2018-11-23 |language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\nPrevious levels of commercial whaling have put the species in danger of extinction in areas such as Cook Inlet, Ungava Bay, the St. Lawrence River and western Greenland. Continued hunting by the native peoples may mean some populations will continue to decline.<ref name=dold /> Northern Canadian sites are the focus of discussions between local communities and the Canadian government, with the objective of permitting sustainable hunting that does not put the species at risk of extinction.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s10745-006-9105-2 |title=Sentient Beings and Wildlife Resources: Inuit, Beluga Whales and Management Regimes in the Canadian Arctic |year=2007 |last1=Tyrrell |first1=Martina |journal=Human Ecology |volume=35 |issue=5 |pages=575\u201386}}</ref>\n\n==== Past ====\nCommercial whaling by European, American and Russian whalers during the 18th and 19th centuries decreased beluga populations in the Arctic.<ref name=ellis /><ref name=\"boltunov\" /><ref name=\"burns\" /> The animals were hunted for their meat and blubber, while the Europeans used the oil from the melon as a [[lubricant]] for [[clock]]s, machinery and lighting in [[lighthouse]]s.<ref name=ellis /> Mineral oil replaced whale oil in the 1860s, but the hunting of these animals continued unabated. In 1863, the cured skin could be used to make [[horse harness]]es, machine belts for [[saw mill]]s and [[shoelaces]]. These manufactured items ensured the hunting of belugas continued for the rest of the 19th century and the beginning of the 20th century.<ref name=encyfr /> The cured skin is the only cetacean skin that is sufficiently thick to be used as [[leather]].<ref name=ellis>{{cite book |author=Ellis, Richard |title=Men and Whales |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=kygGAAAACAAJ |page=560}} |edition=1st |year=1991 |publisher=The Lyons Press |isbn=978-1-55821-696-9 |page=560}}</ref> In fact, their skin is so thick, that it was even used to manufacture some of the first bulletproof vests.<ref>Madison , J. (2014). All About Marine Animals - Animals of the Seas and Oceans .</ref>\n\nRussia had large hunts, peaking in the 1930s at 4,000 per year and the 1960s at 7,000 per year, for a total of 86,000 from 1915 to 2014.<ref name=\"bettridge\" /><ref name=\"boltunov\" /> Canada hunted a total of 54,000 from 1731 to 1970.<ref name=\"cmeps\" /> Between 1868 and 1911, [[Scotland|Scottish]] and American whalers killed more than 20,000 belugas in [[Lancaster Sound]] and [[Davis Strait]].<ref name=ellis />\n\nDuring the 1920s, fishermen in the Saint Lawrence River estuary considered belugas to be a threat to the fishing industry, as they eat large quantities of cod, salmon, tuna and other fish caught by the local fishermen.<ref name=encyfr /> The presence of belugas in the estuary was, therefore, considered to be undesirable; in 1928, the [[Government of Quebec]] offered a reward of 15 dollars for each dead beluga.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=826287&q=Catch+history+and+initial+population+of+white+whales+(Delphinapterus+leucas)+in+the+river+and+gulf+of+St.+Lawrence%2C+eastern+Canada&uid=789801853&setcookie=yes |author1=Reeves, R. R. |author2=Mitchell, E. |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Catch history and initial population of white whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') in the river and gulf of St. Lawrence, eastern Canada |journal=Canadian Field-Naturalist |year=1984 |pages=63\u2013121 |issue=111 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105090537/http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=826287&q=Catch+history+and+initial+population+of+white+whales+(Delphinapterus+leucas)+in+the+river+and+gulf+of+St.+Lawrence%2C+eastern+Canada&uid=789801853&setcookie=yes |archivedate=5 November 2012 |access-date=7 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Quebec Department of Fisheries launched a study into the influence of these cetaceans on local fish populations in 1938. The unrestricted killing of belugas continued into the 1950s, when the supposed voracity of the belugas was found to be overestimated and did not adversely affect fish populations.<ref name=encyfr>{{cite encyclopedia |url=http://www.ameriquefrancaise.org/en/article-294/St._Lawrence_Beluga.html#note11 |author1=Dionne, Suzan |author2=Gourbili\u00e8re, Claire |lastauthoramp=yes |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of French Cultural Heritage in North America |title=St. Lawrence Beluga |year=2007 |accessdate=1 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304055402/http://www.ameriquefrancaise.org/en/article-294/St._Lawrence_Beluga.html#note11#note11 |archivedate=4 March 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[L'Isle-aux-Coudres, Quebec|L'Isle-aux-Coudres]] is the setting for the classic 1963 [[National Film Board of Canada]] documentary ''[[Pour la suite du monde]]'', which depicts a one-off resurrection of the beluga hunt; one animal is caught live, and transported by truck to an aquarium in the big city. The method of capture is akin to [[dolphin drive hunting]].\n\n=== Beluga catches by location ===\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed sortable\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" |Annual table showing the number of belugas caught in Canada, Russia, Greenland and Alaska each year, from 2016 back to 1954\n!scope=\"col\"|Beaufort Sea, Mackenzie, Paulatuk, Ulukhaktok, Canada\n!scope=\"col\"|Nunavut, Canada\n!scope=\"col\"|Nunavik, Quebec, Canada\n!scope=\"col\"|Western Arctic, Russia, hunted for meat\n!scope=\"col\"|Eastern Arctic, Russia, hunted for meat\n!scope=\"col\"|Sea of Okhotsk, Russia, hunted for meat\n!scope=\"col\"|All areas of Russia, live export\n!scope=\"col\"|Year\n!scope=\"col\"|Canada total\n!scope=\"col\"|Greenland\n!scope=\"col\"|USSR+ Russia total\n!scope=\"col\"|USA (Alaska)\n!scope=\"col\"|World total, incomplete\n!scope=\"col\"|Lost at sea as % of caught\n|-\n|||||157||||||||||'''2016'''||157||246||||||||\n|-\n|83||||303||||||||||'''2015'''||386||156||||326||868||\n|-\n|136||||302||||||30||23||'''2014'''||438||317||53||346||1154||2%\n|-\n|92||||207||||||30||23||'''2013'''||299||353||53||367||1072||2%\n|-\n|102||||207||||||30||44||'''2012'''||309||245||74||360||988||4%\n|-\n|72||||207||||||30||33||'''2011'''||279||179||63||288||809||3%\n|-\n|94||||207||||||30||30||'''2010'''||301||222||60||318||901||3%\n|-\n|102||||207||||||30||24||'''2009'''||309||286||54||253||902||6%\n|-\n|79||||207||||||30||25||'''2008'''||286||330||55||254||925||8%\n|-\n|85||||207||||||30||0||'''2007'''||292||145||30||576||1043||2%\n|-\n|126||||207||||||30||20||'''2006'''||333||169||50||226||778||3%\n|-\n|108||||207||||||30||31||'''2005'''||315||231||61||282||889||2%\n|-\n|142||||207||||||30||25||'''2004'''||349||246||55||234||884||8%\n|-\n|125||250||207||||||30||26||'''2003'''||582||510||56||251||1399||9%\n|-\n|89||170||210||||||30||10||'''2002'''||469||510||40||362||1381||3%\n|-\n|96||||370||||||30||22||'''2001'''||466||560||52||416||1494||1%\n|-\n|91||116||243||||||30||10||'''2000'''||450||733||40||280||1503||8%\n|-\n|102||207||243||||||30||23||'''1999'''||552||590||53||217||1412||19%\n|-\n|93||137||243||||||30||23||'''1998'''||473||873||53||342||1741||8%\n|-\n|123||376||243||||||30||23||'''1997'''||742||682||53||276||1753||8%\n|-\n|139||203||243||||||30||23||'''1996'''||585||681||53||389||1708||16%\n|-\n|143||||||||||30||23||'''1995'''||143||960||53||171||1327||11%\n|-\n|149||||||||||30||23||'''1994'''||149||757||53||285||1244||6%\n|-\n|120||||||||||30||23||'''1993'''||120||930||53||369||1472||9%\n|-\n|130||||||||||30||23||'''1992'''||130||1014||53||181||1378||7%\n|-\n|144||||||||||30||23||'''1991'''||144||747||53||315||1259||24%\n|-\n|106||||||||||30||23||'''1990'''||106||933||53||335||1427||22%\n|-\n|156||||||27||||30||23||'''1989'''||156||816||80||13||1065||15%\n|-\n|139||||||7||||30||23||'''1988'''||139||428||60||19||646||19%\n|-\n|174||||||15||||30||23||'''1987'''||174||928||68||22||1192||13%\n|-\n|199||||||192||||30||23||'''1986'''||199||973||245||0||1417||15%\n|-\n|148||||||248||150||30||||'''1985'''||148||887||428||0||1463||17%\n|-\n|156||||||850||150||30||||'''1984'''||156||930||1030||170||2286||20%\n|-\n|102||||||450||150||30||||'''1983'''||102||888||630||235||1855||20%\n|-\n|146||||||116||150||30||||'''1982'''||146||1217||296||335||1994||19%\n|-\n|155||||||294||150||30||||'''1981'''||155||1506||474||209||2344||20%\n|-\n|85||||||368||150||30||||'''1980'''||85||1346||548||249||2228||23%\n|-\n|171||||||200||26||30||||'''1979'''||171||1116||256||138||1681||22%\n|-\n|157||||||63||26||30||||'''1978'''||157||1112||119||177||1565||25%\n|-\n|172||||||1196||26||30||||'''1977'''||172||1264||1252||247||2935||22%\n|-\n|183||||||472||26||30||||'''1976'''||183||1260||528||186||2157||28%\n|-\n|177||||||169||23||30||||'''1975'''||177||995||222||185||1579||23%\n|-\n|152||||||194||23||30||||'''1974'''||152||1149||247||184||1732||25%\n|-\n|212||||||288||23||30||||'''1973'''||212||1451||341||150||2154||23%\n|-\n|134||||||288||||30||||'''1972'''||134||1168||318||180||1800||21%\n|-\n|94||||||612||||30||||'''1971'''||94||913||642||250||1899||23%\n|-\n|137||||||990||||30||||'''1970'''||137||861||1020||200||2218||25%\n|-\n|||||||302||700||30||||'''1969'''||0||1364||1032||170||2566||25%\n|-\n|14||||||30||700||30||||'''1968'''||14||1490||760||150||2414||26%\n|-\n|40||||||274||700||30||||'''1967'''||40||825||1004||225||2094||24%\n|-\n|96||||||3046||700||30||||'''1966'''||96||828||3776||225||4925||23%\n|-\n|70||||||3614||700||30||||'''1965'''||70||595||4344||225||5234||21%\n|-\n|45||||||5952||700||30||||'''1964'''||45||403||6682||225||7355||22%\n|-\n|94||||||2526||700||30||||'''1963'''||94||278||3256||225||3853||21%\n|-\n|96||||||2334||700||30||||'''1962'''||96||409||3064||225||3794||24%\n|-\n|145||||||3500||700||30||||'''1961'''||145||438||4230||300||5113||27%\n|-\n|145||||||6444||700||30||||'''1960'''||145||398||7174||375||8092||22%\n|-\n|||||||1945||700||830||||'''1959'''||||472||3475||450||4397||24%\n|-\n|||||||2103||700||830||||'''1958'''||||411||3633||450||4494||23%\n|-\n|||||||796||700||830||||'''1957'''||||770||2326||450||3546||26%\n|-\n|||||||600||700||830||||'''1956'''||||671||2130||450||3251||25%\n|-\n|||||||329||700||130||||'''1955'''||||507||1159||450||2116||24%\n|-\n|||||||776||700||130||||'''1954'''||||767||1606||450||2823||28%\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| data-sort-value=9999|1960\u20131969<ref name=\"burns\" /> <!--\n-->1970\u201399<ref name=\"harwood\">{{Cite journal |last=Harwood |first=Lois A., Pamela Norton, Billy Day and Patricia A. Hall |date=1 March 2002 |title=The Harvest of Beluga Whales in Canada's Western Arctic: Hunter-Based Monitoring of the Size and Composition of the Catch (has data through 1984)|url=http://arctic.journalhosting.ucalgary.ca/arctic/