Sonja K. |last4=Snow |first4=Kathleen |last5=MacPhee |first5=Shannon A. |last6=McNicholl |first6=Darcy G. |last7=Choy |first7=Emily S. |last8=Giraldo |first8=Carolina |last9=Hornby |first9=Claire A. |date=2018-02-21 |title=Diet and feeding observations from an unusual beluga harvest in 2014 near Ulukhaktok, Northwest Territories, Canada |journal=Arctic Science |volume=4 |issue=3 |pages=421\u2013431 |doi=10.1139/as-2017-0046 |issn=2368-7460|hdl=1807/88141 |url=https://archimer.ifremer.fr/doc/00428/53927/ |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n| data-sort-value=9999|Arviat<ref name=\"suluk\">{{Cite journal |last=SULUK |first=THOMAS K., and SHERRIE L. BLAKNEY |year=2008 |title=Land Claims and Resistance to the Management of Harvester Activities in Nunavut |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic61-S-62.pdf |journal=Arctic |volume=61 |issue=5 |pages=62\u201370 |via=University of Calgary |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921214017/http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/arctic61-s-62.pdf |archivedate=21 September 2017 |doi=10.14430/arctic102|hdl=10535/5552 }}</ref>\n| 1996\u20132002<ref name=\"kishigami\">{{Cite journal |last=Kishigami |first=Noboru |year=2005 |title=Co-Management of Beluga Whales in Nunavik (Arctic Quebec), Canada |url=https://minpaku.repo.nii.ac.jp/?action=repository_action_common_download&item_id=2673&item_no=1&attribute_id=18&file_no=1 |journal=Senri Ethnological Studies |volume=67 |pages=121\u2013144 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503204950/https://minpaku.repo.nii.ac.jp/?action=repository_action_common_download&item_id=2673&item_no=1&attribute_id=18&file_no=1 |archivedate=3 May 2018}}</ref>\n2003\u201316<ref name=\"nunatsiak\">{{Cite news |url=http://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/65674nunaviks_beluga_season_closes_early/ |title=Nunatsiaq News 2016-08-22: NEWS: Nunavik's beluga season closes early |last=Rogers |first=Sarah |date=22 August 2016 |work=Nunatsiaq News |access-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712214301/http://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/65674nunaviks_beluga_season_closes_early/ |archivedate=12 July 2018}}</ref>\n| data-sort-value=9999|1954\u201399<ref name=\"boltunov\">{{Cite journal |author=Boltunov, Andrei N. and Belikov, Stanislav E. |date=2002 |title=Belugas (''Delphinapterus leucas'') of the Barents, Kara and Laptev seas |url=https://septentrio.uit.no/index.php/NAMMCOSP/article/viewFile/2842/2696 |journal=NAMMCO Sci. Publ. |volume=4 |pages=149\u2013168 |via=Septentrio Academic Publishing, Arctic University of Norway|doi=10.7557/3.2842 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n| data-sort-value=9999|1954\u20131985 cites Russian papers<ref name=\"burns\" />\n| NMFS cites Russian paper<ref name=\"bettridge\">{{Cite web |url=https://swfsc.noaa.gov/publications/CR/2016/2016Bettridge.pdf|title=Status Review of the Sakhalin Bay-Amur River Beluga Whale (''Delphinapterus leucas'') under the Marine Mammal Protection Act |last=Bettridge |first=Shannon, Robert L. Brownell Jr., Melissa Andersen Garcia, Rod C. Hobbs, Cheri L. McCarty, Richard D. Methot Jr., Debra L. Palka, Patricia E. Rosel, Kathryn S. Swails, and Barbara L. Taylor |date=1 March 2016 |website=cites Shpak, Meschersky, Hobbs, Andrews, Glazov, Chelintsev, Kuznetsova, Solovyev, Nazarenko, Michaud, and Mukhametov. 2011. Current status of the Sakhalin-Amur beluga aggregation (The Okhotsk Sea, Russia): sustainability assessment. Report for 2007\u20132010 stages: Report presented at IUCN Independent Scientific Review Panel, Chicago, 6\u20137 March 2011 (unpublished). 68p and 5 Appendices. |access-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430213702/http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/species/documents/status_review_of_sakhalin_bay-amur_river_beluga_whale.pdf |archivedate=30 April 2017}} This table uses their \"high\" estimate, since they say, page 23: \"The high take scenario is considered the better of the two because it accounts for times when takes are known to have occurred but are not documented. Additionally, we did not account for beluga whales that are struck and lost because these data are not available, so the high take option may even be an underestimate.\"</ref>\n| data-sort-value=9999|Western<ref name=\"boltunov\" /> Okhotsk<ref name=\"bettridge\" />\n| data-sort-value=9999|'''Sources'''\n| data-sort-value=9999|Total of columns at left, incomplete\n| data-sort-value=9999|1954\u20132016<ref name=\"catch\">{{Cite paper |last=Heide-Jorgensen |first=M.P. and E. Garde |date=1 March 2017 |title=Catch statistics for belugas in Greenland 1862 to 2016 |via=NAMMCO/JCNB Joint Working Group on narwhals and belugas, Copenhagen}} Paper is not online. This table uses their \"high\" estimate (which includes struck and lost), without harvests from ice entrapments (which would die even if not harvested).</ref>\n| data-sort-value=9999|Total of columns at left, incomplete\n| data-sort-value=9999|{{small|1954\u201384<!--\n--><ref name=\"burns\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boem.gov/ESPIS/0/81.pdf |title=Investigations of Belukha Whales in Coastal Waters of Western and Northern Alaska II. Biology and Ecology |last=Burns |first=John J. and Glenn A. Seaman |date=1 November 1986 |series=Outer Continental Shelf Environmental Assessment Program |publisher=Alaska Department of Fish and Game |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327213932/https://www.boem.gov/ESPIS/0/81.pdf |archivedate=27 March 2018}}</ref> <!--\n-->1987\u201390 Cook Inlet<ref name=\"stanek\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/techpap/tp232.pdf |title=The Subsistence Use of Beluga Whale in Cook Inlet by Alaska Natives, 1993 |last=Stanek |first=Ronald |date=1 July 1994 |website=Alaska Dept of Fish and Game |access-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809062040/http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/TechPap/tp232.pdf |archivedate=9 August 2017}}</ref> <!--\n-->1990\u20132011<ref name=\"afsc\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.afsc.noaa.gov/maps/ESSR/subsistence/default.htm |title=Participation in subsistence fishing by residents-Beluga harvested by residents (downloadable data) |year=2011 |access-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180327212632/https://www.afsc.noaa.gov/maps/ESSR/subsistence/default.htm |archivedate=27 March 2018}}</ref> <!--\n-->2012\u20132015 +Cook Inlet<ref name=\"sar2017\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/webdam/download/64132759 |title=Alaska Marine Mammal Stock Assessments, 2017 (draft) |last=Muto |first=M.M., V. T. Helker, R. P. Angliss, B. A. Allen, P. L. Boveng, J.M. Breiwick, M. F. Cameron, P. J. Clapham, S. P. Dahle, M. E. Dahlheim, B. S. Fadely, M.C. Ferguson, L. W. Fritz, R. C. Hobbs, Y. V. Ivashchenko, A. S. Kennedy, J.M. London, S. A. Mizroch, R. R. Ream, E. L. Richmond, K. E. W. Shelden, R. G. Towell, P. R. Wade, J. M. Waite, and A. N. Zerbini |year=2017 |website=Marine Mammal Laboratory, Alaska Fisheries Science Center, NMFS, NOAA |access-date=8 April 2018}}</ref><!--\n--><ref name=\"sar-draft\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/national/marine-mammal-protection/draft-marine-mammal-stock-assessment-reports |title=Draft Marine Mammal Stock Assessment Reports, NOAA Fisheries |last=Fisheries |first=NOAA |date=31 January 2018 |website=fisheries.noaa.gov |access-date=8 April 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180428225802/https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/national/marine-mammal-protection/draft-marine-mammal-stock-assessment-reports |archivedate=28 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n| data-sort-value=9999|Total of other columns\n| data-sort-value=9999|{{small|Greenland source 1954\u20131999, Beaufort source 2000\u20132012}}\n|}\n\n=== Predation ===\n\nDuring the winter, belugas commonly become trapped in the ice without being able to escape to open water, which may be several kilometres away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/173781/3/ |author=Hern\u00e1ndez, Clara |language=Spanish |date=17 November 2006 |publisher=20 minutos.es \u2013 Internacional |title=Un grupo de cazadores matar\u00e1 en Canad\u00e1 a cerca de 80 belugas que han quedado atrapadas por el hielo}}</ref> Polar bears take particular advantage of these situations and are able to locate the belugas using their sense of smell. The bears swipe at the belugas and drag them onto the ice to eat them.<ref name=audubon /> They are able to capture large individuals in this way; in one documented incident, a bear weighing between 150 and 180&nbsp;kg was able to capture an animal that weighed 935&nbsp;kg.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic26-2-162.pdf |title=Polar Bear Predation on Beluga in the Canadian Arctic |author=Freeman, Milton M. R. |publisher=McMaster University, Hamilton, Ontario |accessdate=12 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100415040930/http://pubs.aina.ucalgary.ca/arctic/Arctic26-2-162.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nKiller whales are able to capture both young and adult belugas.<ref name=audubon /> They live in all the seas of the world and share the same habitat as belugas in the sub-Arctic region. Attacks on belugas by killer whales have been reported in the waters of Greenland, Russia, Canada and Alaska.<ref name=shelden>{{cite journal |url=http://www.fakr.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga/MMSKillerwhaleBeluga.pdf |vauthors=Shelden KE, Rugh DJ, Mahoney BA, Dahlheim ME |title=Killer whale predation on belugas in Cook Inlet, Alaska: Implications for a depleted population |journal=Mar. Mammal Sci. |volume=19 |pages=529\u2013544 |doi=10.1111/j.1748-7692.2003.tb01319.x |year=2003 |issue=3 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224211121/http://www.fakr.noaa.gov/protectedresources/whales/beluga/MMSKillerwhaleBeluga.pdf |archivedate=24 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=1560717&q=beluga+killer+whale+predation&uid=789731160&setcookie=yes |vauthors=Lowry LF, Nelson RR, Frost KJ |title=Observations of killer whales, ''Orcinus orca'', in western Alaska: Sightings, strandings, and predation on other marine mammals |journal=Ont. Field-Nat |volume=101 |year=1987 |pages=6\u201312 |issue=1 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105090517/http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=1560717&q=beluga+killer+whale+predation&uid=789731160&setcookie=yes |archivedate=5 November 2012}}</ref> A number of killings have been recorded in Cook Inlet, and experts are concerned the predation by killer whales will impede the recovery of this subpopulation, which has already been badly depleted by hunting.<ref name=shelden /> The killer whales arrive at the beginning of August, but the belugas are occasionally able to hear their presence and evade them. The groups near to or under the sea ice have a degree of protection, as the killer whale's large dorsal fin, up to 2&nbsp;m in length, impedes their movement under the ice and does not allow them to get sufficiently close to the breathing holes in the ice.<ref name=paine /> Beluga whale behavior under killer whale predation makes them vulnerable to hunters. When killer whales are present, large numbers of beluga whales congregate in the shallows for protection, which allows them to be hunted in droves.\n\n=== Contamination ===\n[[File:Beluga premier.gov.ru-8.jpeg|thumb|right|Russian scientists working on the White Whale Program place transmitters onto whales in Sea of Okhotsk]]\nThe beluga is considered an excellent sentinel species (indicator of environment health and changes), because it is long-lived, at the top of the food web, bears large amounts of fat and blubber, relatively well-studied for a cetacean, and still somewhat common.\n\nHuman pollution can be a threat to belugas' health when they congregate in river estuaries. Chemical substances such as [[DDT]] and heavy metals such as [[lead]], [[Mercury (element)|mercury]] and [[cadmium]] have been found in individuals of the Saint Lawrence River population.<ref name=beland /> Local beluga carcasses contain so many contaminants, they are treated as toxic waste.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oceanlink.info/ocean_matters/pollution.html |title=Marine Pollution: Causes and Effects |publisher=Bamfield Marine Sciences Centre Public Education Program |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130218045627/http://www.oceanlink.info/ocean_matters/pollution.html |archivedate=18 February 2013}}</ref> Levels of [[polychlorinated biphenyls]] between 240 and 800 [[Parts per million|ppm]] have been found in belugas' [[brain]]s, [[liver]] and [[muscle]]s, with the highest levels found in males.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0141-1136(98)00107-X |title=Polychlorinated biphenyls and organochlorine compounds in brain, liver and muscle of beluga whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') from the Arctic and St. Lawrence estuary |year=1999 |last1=Metcalfe |first1=C |last2=Metcalfe |first2=T |last3=Ray |first3=S |last4=Paterson |first4=G |last5=Koenig |first5=B |journal=Marine Environmental Research |volume=47 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201315}}</ref> These levels are significantly greater than those found in Arctic populations.<ref name=smith>{{cite book |author=Smith, T. G. |author2=D. J. St. Aubin |author3=J. R. Geraci |last-author-amp=yes |title=Advances in Research on the Beluga Whale, ''Delphinapterus leucas'' |year=1990 |publisher=Department of Fisheries and Oceans |location=Ottawa |isbn=978-0-660-13817-6|ol=7626804M }}</ref> These substances have a proven adverse effect on these cetaceans, as they cause [[cancer]]s, reproductive diseases and the deterioration of the [[immune system]], making individuals more susceptible to [[pneumonia]]s, [[ulcer]]s, [[cyst]]s, [[tumour]]s and bacterial [[infection]]s.<ref name=smith /> Although the populations that inhabit the river estuaries run the greatest risk of contamination, high levels of [[zinc]], [[cadmium]], mercury and [[selenium]] have also been found in the muscles, livers and [[kidney]]s of animals that live in the open sea.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/BF00233702 |title=Zinc, cadmium, mercury and selenium in minke whales, belugas and narwhals from West Greenland |year=1990 |last1=Hansen |first1=Carstenthye |last2=Nielsen |first2=Christianovergaard |last3=Dietz |first3=Rune |last4=Hansen |first4=Martinmunk |journal=Polar Biology |volume=10 |issue=7 |pages=529\u201339}}</ref>\n\nFrom a sample of 129 beluga adults from the Saint Lawrence River examined between 1983 and 1999, a total of 27% had suffered cancer.<ref name=\"cancermedvet\">{{Cite journal |doi=10.1289/ehp.02110285 |pmid=11882480 |pmc=1240769 |title=Cancer in Wildlife, a Case Study: Beluga from the St. Lawrence Estuary, Qu\u00e9bec, Canada |journal=Environmental Health Perspectives |volume=110 |issue=3 |pages=285\u201392 |year=2002 |last1=Martineau |first1=D. |last2=Lemberger |first2=K. |last3=Dallaire |first3=A. |last4=Labelle |first4=P. |last5=Lipscomb |first5=T. P. |last6=Michel |first6=P. |last7=Mikaelian |first7=I.}}</ref> This is a higher percentage than that documented for other populations of this species and is much higher than for other cetaceans and for the majority of terrestrial mammals; in fact, the rate is only comparable to the levels found in humans and some domesticated animals.<ref name=\"cancermedvet\" /> For example, the rate of intestinal cancer in the sample is much higher than for humans. This condition is thought to be directly related to environmental contamination, in this case by [[polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbon]]s, and coincides with the high incidence of this disease in humans residing in the area.<ref name=\"cancermedvet\" /> The prevalence of tumours suggests the contaminants identified in the animals that inhabit the estuary are having a direct [[carcinogenic]] effect or they are at least causing an immunological deterioration that is reducing the inhabitants' resistance to the disease.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1177/030098589403100406 |pmid=7941233 |title=Tumors in St. Lawrence Beluga Whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') |journal=Veterinary Pathology |volume=31 |issue=4 |pages=444\u20139 |year=1994 |last1=Guise |first1=S. D. |last2=Lagace |first2=A. |last3=Beland |first3=P.|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nIndirect human disturbance may also be a threat. While some populations tolerate small boats, most actively try to avoid ships. [[Whale-watching]] has become a booming activity in the St. Lawrence and Churchill River areas, and acoustic contamination from this activity appears to have an effect on belugas. For example, a correlation appears to exist between the passage of belugas across the mouth of the Saguenay River, which has decreased by 60%, and the increase in the use of recreational motorboats in the area.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Caron LM, Sergeant DE |title=Yearly variation in the frequency of passage of beluga whales (''Delphinapterus leucas'') at the mouth of the Saguenay River, Quebec, over the past decade |journal=Nat Can |volume=115 |year=1988 |pages=111\u2013116 |issue=2}}</ref> A dramatic decrease has also been recorded in the number of calls between animals (decreasing from 3.4 to 10.5 calls/min to 0 or <1) after exposure to the noise produced by ships, the effect being most persistent and pronounced with larger ships such as [[Ferry|ferries]] than with smaller boats.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.beamreach.org/research/acoustics/compensation/lesage+99.pdf |title=The Effect of Vessel Noise on the Vocal Behavior of Belugas in the St. Lawrence River Estuary, Canada |journal=Marine Mammal Science |volume=15 |date=January 1999 |pages=65\u201384 |doi=10.1111/j.1748-7692.1999.tb00782.x |issue=1 |last1=Lesage |first1=Veronique |last2=Barrette |first2=Cyrille |last3=Kingsley |first3=Michael C. S. |last4=Sjare |first4=Becky |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202001418/http://www.beamreach.org/research/acoustics/compensation/lesage+99.pdf |archivedate=2 February 2012}}</ref> Belugas can detect the presence of large ships (for example [[icebreaker]]s) up to 50&nbsp;km away, and they move rapidly in the opposite direction or perpendicular to the ship following the edge of the sea ice for distances of up to 80&nbsp;km to avoid them. The presence of shipping produces avoidance behaviour, causing deeper dives for feeding, the break-up of groups, and asynchrony in dives.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=2534036&q=Reactions+of+belugas,+Delphinapterus+leucas+,+and+narwhals,+Monodon+monoceros,+to+ice-breaking+ships+in+the+Canadian+High+Arctic&uid=789716584&setcookie=yes |vauthors=Finley KJ, Miller GW, Davis RA, Greene CR |title=Reactions of belugas, ''Delphinapterus leucas'', and narwhals, ''Monodon monoceros'', to ice-breaking ships in the Canadian High Arctic. In \"Advances in research on the beluga whale, ''Delphinapterus leucas''\" |journal=Can Bull Fish Aquat Sci |volume=224 |year=1990 |pages=97\u2013117 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105090530/http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=2534036&q=Reactions+of+belugas,+Delphinapterus+leucas+,+and+narwhals,+Monodon+monoceros,+to+ice-breaking+ships+in+the+Canadian+High+Arctic&uid=789716584&setcookie=yes |archivedate=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Pathogens ===\n\nAs with any animal population, a number of pathogens cause death and disease in belugas, including [[virus]]es, [[bacteria]], [[protozoa]]ns and [[fungi]], which mainly cause skin, intestinal and respiratory infections.<ref name=dead>{{cite web |url=http://www.seaworld.org/infobooks/beluga/bedeath.html |author=Sea World.org |title=Beluga Whales \u2013 Longevity and Causes of Death |year=2002 |accessdate=30 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619232847/http://seaworld.org/infobooks/Beluga/bedeath.html |archivedate=19 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Papillomaviridae|Papillomaviruses]] have been found in the stomachs of belugas in the Saint Lawrence River. Animals in this location have also been recorded as suffering infections caused by [[Herpesviridae|herpesviruses]] and in certain cases to be suffering from [[encephalitis]] caused by the protozoan ''[[Sarcocystis]]''. Cases have been recorded of [[ciliate]] protozoa colonising the spiracle of certain individuals, but they are not thought to be pathogens or are not very harmful.<ref name=dierauf />{{rp|26, 303, 359}}\n\nThe bacterium ''[[Erysipelothrix rhusiopathiae]]'', which probably comes from eating infected fish, poses a threat to belugas kept in captivity, causing [[anorexia (symptom)|anorexia]] and [[dermal]] plaques and [[lesion]]s that can lead to [[sepsis]].<ref name=dierauf />{{rp|26, 303, 359}} This condition can cause death if it is not diagnosed and treated in time with [[antibiotic]]s such as [[ciprofloxacin]].<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1002/zoo.1430120510 |title=Successful treatment of suspected erysipelas septicemia in a beluga whale (''Delphinapterus leucas'') |year=1993 |last1=Calle |first1=Paul P. |last2=Kenny |first2=David E. |last3=Cook |first3=Robert A. |journal=Zoo Biology |volume=12 |issue=5 |pages=483\u201390}}</ref><ref name=dierauf /><ref name=dierauf />{{rp|316\u20137}}\n\nA study of infections caused by [[parasitic worms]] in a number of individuals of both sexes found the presence of larvae from a species from the genus ''Contracaecum'' in their [[stomach]]s and [[intestine]]s, ''[[Anisakis]] simplex'' in their stomachs, ''Pharurus pallasii'' in their ear canals, ''Hadwenius seymouri'' in their intestines and ''Leucasiella arctica'' in their rectums.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.7589/0090-3558-22.3.440 |title=Helminths of the Beluga Whale (''Delphinapterus leucas'') from the Mackenzie River Delta, Northwest Territories |year=1986 |last1=Wazura |first1=K. W. |last2=Strong |first2=J. T. |last3=Glenn |first3=C. L. |last4=Bush |first4=Albert O. |journal=Journal of Wildlife Diseases |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=440\u20132 |pmid=3735598}}</ref>\n\n== Relationship with humans ==\n\n=== Captivity ===\nBelugas were among the first whale species to be kept in captivity. The first beluga was shown at [[Barnum's American Museum|Barnum's Museum]] in [[New York City]] in 1861.<ref name='New York Tribune'>{{cite web |url=http://chnm.gmu.edu/lostmuseum/lm/190/ |title=The Whales, New York Tribune, August 9, 1861 |accessdate=5 December 2011 |date=9 August 1861 |work=New York Tribune |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030607052153/http://chnm.gmu.edu/lostmuseum/lm/190/ |archivedate=7 June 2003 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> For most of the 20th century, Canada was the predominant source for belugas destined for exhibition. Throughout the early 1960s, belugas were taken from the [[St. Lawrence River]] estuary. In 1967, the Churchill River estuary became the main source from which belugas were captured. This continued until 1992, when the practice was banned.<ref name=\"cmeps\">{{cite web |url=http://webpages.charter.net/hrynyshyn/pdfs/Beluga_Report_web2006.pdf |title=Beluga Whales in Captivity |accessdate=26 December 2014 |year=2006 |work=Special Report on Captivity 2006 |publisher=Canadian Marine Environment Protection Society |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226215306/http://webpages.charter.net/hrynyshyn/pdfs/Beluga_Report_web2006.pdf |archivedate=26 December 2014}}</ref> Since Canada ceased to be the supplier of these animals, Russia has become the largest provider.<ref name=\"cmeps\" /> Individuals are caught in the Amur River delta and the far eastern seas of the country, and then are either transported domestically to aquaria in [[Moscow]], [[St. Petersburg]] and [[Sochi]], or exported to foreign nations, including China<ref name=\"master\" /> and formerly Canada.<ref name=\"cmeps\" /> Canada has now banned the practice of holding new animals in captivity.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/06/11/731570415/canada-bans-keeping-whales-and-dolphins-in-captivity |title=Canada Bans Keeping Whales And Dolphins In Captivity|last=Held|first=Amy |date=June 11, 2019 |work=npr|access-date=2019-09-30 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Starkhammar2012.png|thumb|Beluga aims echolocation beam to choose a spot on an acoustic \"touch screen\" of hydrophones in the water]]\nTo provide some enrichment while in captivity, aquaria train belugas to perform behaviours for the public<ref name=\"mysticbelugas\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mysticaquarium.org/animals-and-exhibits/species-of-the-month/731-beluga-whales |title=Beluga Whales |publisher=Mystic Aquarium |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013085934/http://www.mysticaquarium.org/animals-and-exhibits/species-of-the-month/731-beluga-whales |archivedate=13 October 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and for medical exams, such as blood draws,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mysticaquarium.org/animals-and-exhibits/species-of-the-month/1002-speices-of-the-month-juno |title=Species of the Month, Juno |publisher=Mystic Aquarium |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119224652/http://www.mysticaquarium.org/animals-and-exhibits/species-of-the-month/1002-speices-of-the-month-juno |archivedate=19 January 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[ultrasound]],<ref name=\"georgiaultrasound\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E0WR6cXMC2g |title=Beluga Whales Training |publisher=GeorgiaAquarium |date=4 March 2008 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316111445/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E0WR6cXMC2g |archivedate=16 March 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> providing toys,<ref name=\"mysticbelugas\" /> and allowing the public to play recorded or live music.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/03/mariachi-band-plays-for-beluga-whale_n_917178.html |title=Mariachi Band Serenades Beluga Whale |work=HuffPost |date=3 August 2011 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129074250/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/08/03/mariachi-band-plays-for-beluga-whale_n_917178.html |archivedate=29 November 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1960 and 1992, the [[United States Navy]] carried out a program that included the study of [[marine mammal]]s' abilities with echolocation, with the objective of improving the detection of underwater objects. The program started with dolphins, but a large number of belugas were also used from 1975 onwards.<ref name=navybel /> The program included training these mammals to carry equipment and material to divers working under water, the location of lost objects, surveillance of ships and [[submarine]]s, and underwater monitoring using cameras held in their mouths.<ref name=navybel>{{cite web |title=The Story of Navy Dolphins |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/whales/etc/navycron.html |publisher=[[PBS]] |accessdate=12 October 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081230160530/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/whales/etc/navycron.html |archivedate=30 December 2008}}</ref> A similar program was implemented by the [[Soviet Navy]] during the [[Cold War]], in which belugas were also trained for anti[[Naval mine|mining]] operations in Arctic waters.<ref name=beland>{{cite book |title=Beluga: A Farewell to Whales |author=Beland, Pierre |publisher=The Lyons Press |edition=1 |year=1996 |isbn=978-1-55821-398-2 |page=[https://archive.org/details/belugafarewellto0000bela/page/224 224] |url=https://archive.org/details/belugafarewellto0000bela/page/224 }}</ref> It is possible this program continues within the [[Russian Navy]], as on April 24, 2019 a [[Hvaldimir|tame beluga whale wearing a Russian equipment harness]] was found by fishermen near the Norwegian island of [[Ing\u00f8ya]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.dagbladet.no/nyheter/reddet-russisk-militaerhval-pa-norgesbesok/71018944 |title=Reddet russisk \"milit\u00e6rhval\" p\u00e5 norgesbes\u00f8k |date=April 27, 2019 |work= Dagbladet |access-date=2019-04-29 |language=no}}</ref>\n\nBelugas released from captivity have difficulties adapting to life in the wild, but if not fed by humans they may have a chance to join a group of wild belugas and learn to feed themselves, according to Audun Rikardsen of the [[University of Troms\u00f8]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/may/02/russian-spy-whale-has-defected-to-norway-locals-claim|title=As experts fear for its survival, Tufjord residents told not to feed beluga so that it can learn to forage|author= Jon Henley|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2019-05-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, a sanctuary in Iceland was established for belugas that retired from a marine park in China. A British company, Merlin Entertainments, bought the park in 2012, as part of an Australian chain, and it is one of their largest aquaria.<ref name=\"ft\">{{Cite news |url=https://markets.ft.com/data/announce/detail?dockey=1323-13740620-55H9AIUR7PLHT0P2OOQJU6T6GG |title=Merlin Entertainments plc - 2018 Interim Results \u2013 Company Announcement - FT.com |date=2 August 2018 |work=Financial Times |access-date=2018-11-21 }}</ref> Merlin has a policy against captive cetaceans, so they sponsored a 32,000-square-metre sea pen as a sanctuary. The 12-year-old belugas, caught in Russia and raised in captivity, do not know how to live in the wild.<ref name=\"pall\">{{Cite news |url=http://icelandreview.com/news/2018/06/28/beluga-whales-train-sanctuary-iceland |title=Beluga Whales Train for Sanctuary in Iceland |last=\u00c1stvaldsson |first=J\u00f3hann P\u00e1ll |date=2018-06-28 |work=Iceland Review |access-date=2018-11-21 }}</ref><ref name=\"wong\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.star2.com/living/2018/07/10/worlds-first-open-water-sanctuary-for-beluga-whales-in-iceland-to-open-in-spring-2019/ |title=World's First Open Water Sanctuary For Beluga Whales To Open Spring 2019 In Iceland |last=Wong |first=Li Za |date=2018-07-10 |work=Star2.com |access-date=2018-11-21 }}</ref> The cost is variously listed as ISK 3,000,000 (US$24,000) or US$27,000,000.<ref name=\"pall\" /> Merlin was owned until 2015 by [[Blackstone Group]], which also owned [[SeaWorld]]<ref name=\"sanct\">{{Cite web |url=https://whalesanctuaryproject.org/merlin-entertainment-seeks-move-belugas-sanctuary/ |title=Merlin Entertainment Seeks to Move Belugas to Sanctuary |last=Mountain |first=Michael |date=2017-06-15 |website=The Whale Sanctuary Project |access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref> until selling its last stake in 2017 to a Chinese company which will use SeaWorld's expertise to expand in China;<ref name=\"zho\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.sciencesetavenir.fr/animaux/animaux-marins/les-parcs-a-theme-controverses-seaworld-arrivent-bientot-en-asie_111629 |title=Les parcs \u00e0 th\u00e8me controvers\u00e9s SeaWorld arrivent bient\u00f4t en Asie |date=March 27, 2017 |work=Sciences et Avenir |access-date=2018-11-23 |language=fr}}</ref> SeaWorld still keeps belugas in captivity.\n\n[[File:WIKI SEA WORLD FL 2.jpg|thumb|right|Beluga whales in an aquarium interacting with trainers|alt=Photo of two white whales cheek-to-cheek with two trainers]]\nBelugas are the only whale species kept in aquaria and [[marine park]]s. They are displayed across North America, Europe and Asia.<ref name=\"cmeps\" /> As of 2006, 58 belugas were held in captivity in Canada and the United States, and 42 deaths in US captivity had been reported up to that time. A single specimen costs up to US$100,000, although the price has now dropped to US$70,000.<ref name=\"pfvl\">{{Cite news |url=http://portofranko-vl.ru/ru/publication/beluhi-uplyli-v-kitay |title=Belugas \"floated away\" to China. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0443\u0445\u0438 \"\u0443\u043f\u043b\u044b\u043b\u0438\" \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0439. \u0417\u0430 \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043d \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0424\u0413\u0411\u041d\u0423 \"\u0422\u0418\u041d\u0420\u041e-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\" \u041b\u0435\u0432 \u0411\u043e\u0447\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432? |work=Porto Franko, Vladivostok |access-date=2018-11-23}} Article says belugas cost USD 70,000 or 60,000, while orcas cost USD 7 million, while another article says orcas cost USD 1 million (RUB 67 million): https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2018/09/14/77814-orfey-2005-g-r-1-sht-gratsiya-2009-g-r-1-sht</ref><ref <ref name=\"cmeps\" /> As of January 2018, according to the nonprofit Ceta Base, which tracks belugas and dolphins under human care, there were 81 captive belugas in Canada and the United States, and unknown numbers in the rest of the world.<ref name=\"cetabase\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cetabase.org/captive/cetacean/us-canada |title=Ceta Base \u2013 Captive Cetacean Database \u2013 Cetacean Inventory \u2022 U.S. & Canada |date=January 31, 2018 |website=cetabase.org |language=en-US |access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref> <ref name=\"pfvl\">{{Cite news |url=http://portofranko-vl.ru/ru/publication/beluhi-uplyli-v-kitay |title=Belugas \"floated away\" to China. \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0443\u0445\u0438 \"\u0443\u043f\u043b\u044b\u043b\u0438\" \u0432 \u041a\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0439. \u0417\u0430 \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043d \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0424\u0413\u0411\u041d\u0423 \"\u0422\u0418\u041d\u0420\u041e-\u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\" \u041b\u0435\u0432 \u0411\u043e\u0447\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432? |work=Porto Franko, Vladivostok |access-date=2018-11-23}} Article says belugas cost USD 70,000 or 60,000, while orcas cost USD 7 million, while another article says orcas cost USD 1 million (RUB 67 million): https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2018/09/14/77814-orfey-2005-g-r-1-sht-gratsiya-2009-g-r-1-sht</ref><ref name=\"rub\">{{Cite web |url=https://uk.whales.org/news/2017/03/arrests-made-in-russia-following-illegal-whale-trafficking-scandal |title=Arrests made in Russia following illegal whale trafficking scandal |date=2017-03-21|website=WDC, Whale and Dolphin Conservation |language=en |access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> The beluga's popularity with visitors reflects its attractive colour and its range of [[facial expression]]s. The latter is possible because while most cetacean \"smiles\" are fixed, the extra movement afforded by the beluga's unfused cervical vertebrae allows a greater range of apparent expression.<ref name=\"Bonner, W.N. 17, 23\u201324\" />\n\nMost belugas found in aquaria are caught in the wild, as captive-breeding programs have not had much success so far.<ref name=\"zoos\">{{cite web |url=http://www.waza.org/en/zoo/visit-the-zoo/aquatic-mammals-1254385523/delphinapterus-leucas |title=Beluga (''Delphinapterus leucas'')Facts \u2013 Distribution \u2013 In the Zoo |accessdate=5 December 2011 |publisher=WAZA : World Association of Zoos and Aquariums |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210101419/http://www.waza.org/en/zoo/visit-the-zoo/aquatic-mammals-1254385523/delphinapterus-leucas |archivedate=10 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> For example, despite best efforts, as of 2010, only two male whales had been successfully used as stud animals in the [[Association of Zoos and Aquariums]] <!-- (AZA) --> beluga population, Nanuq at [[SeaWorld San Diego]] and Naluark at the [[Shedd Aquarium]] in [[Chicago]], USA. Nanuq has fathered 10 calves, five of which survived birth.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nanuq |url=http://www.cetacousin.bplaced.net/whale/north/facts/vananuq.html |publisher=Cetacousin |accessdate=9 September 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Naluark at Shedd Aquarium has fathered four living offspring.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beluga Whale Calf Born at Shedd Aquarium |url=http://wildexplorer.org/ |publisher=Association of Zoos and Aquariums |accessdate=9 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914202409/http://wildexplorer.org/ |archivedate=14 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Naluark was relocated to the [[Mystic Aquarium]] in the hope that he would breed with two of their females,<ref>{{cite web |title=Male Beluga Whale Arrives at Mystic Aquarium |url=http://www.mysticaquarium.org/newsroom/press-releases/827-male-beluga-whale-arrives-at-mystic-aquarium |publisher=Mystic Aquarium |accessdate=9 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120005836/http://www.mysticaquarium.org/newsroom/press-releases/827-male-beluga-whale-arrives-at-mystic-aquarium |archivedate=20 January 2012}}</ref> but he did not, and in 2016 he was moved to SeaWorld Orlando.<ref name=\"pedicini\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/business/tourism/os-seaworld-belugas-20160208-story.html |title=SeaWorld switches beluga whales |last=Pedicini |first=Sandra |work=OrlandoSentinel.com |access-date=2018-11-22 |language=en-US}}</ref> The first beluga calf born in captivity in Europe was born in [[L'Oceanogr\u00e0fic]] marine park in [[Valencia]], [[Spain]], in November 2006.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/168936/0/nace/beluga/oceanografico |title=Nace la primera cr\u00eda de ballena beluga en cautividad en Europa |language=Spanish |author=Inmaculada Sanz |publisher=Noticias 20minutos |date=3 November 2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110207184601/http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/168936/0/nace/beluga/oceanografico/ |archivedate=7 February 2011 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, the calf died 25 days later after suffering [[Metabolism|metabolic]] complications, infections and not being able to feed properly.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/177080/0/beluga/muere/valencia/ |title=Muere la ballena beluga que naci\u00f3 hace 25 d\u00edas en el Oceanogr\u00e1fico de Valencia |language=Spanish |author=Noticias 20minutos Valencia |date=27 November 2006 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701045309/http://www.20minutos.es/noticia/177080/0/beluga/muere/valencia/ |archivedate=1 July 2013}}</ref> A second calf was born on 16 November 2016, and was successfully maintained by artificial feeding based on enriched milk.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eldiario.es/cultura/tecnologia/Kylu-beluga-Oceanografic-Valencia-superluna_0_602290272.html |title=Kylu, la beluga que naci\u00f3 en el Oceanogr\u00e0fic de Valencia un d\u00eda de superluna |language=Spanish |author=eldiario.es |date=16 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170117095035/http://www.eldiario.es/cultura/tecnologia/Kylu-beluga-Oceanografic-Valencia-superluna_0_602290272.html |archivedate=17 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 during a free-diving competition in a tank of icy water in [[Harbin]], [[China]], a captive beluga brought a cramp-paralysed diver from the bottom of the pool up to the surface by holding her foot in its mouth, saving the diver's life.<ref>{{cite web |title=Beluga Whale Saves Diver |url=http://www.treehugger.com/files/2009/08/amazing-beluga-whale-rescues-diver.php |author=Lepisto, Christine |date=2 August 2009 |accessdate=31 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330030544/http://www.treehugger.com/files/2009/08/amazing-beluga-whale-rescues-diver.php |archivedate=30 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wal Rettet Ertrinkende Taucherin! |url=http://www.blick.ch/news/ausland/wal-rettet-ertrinkende-taucherin-124805 |accessdate=27 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802184546/http://www.blick.ch/news/ausland/wal-rettet-ertrinkende-taucherin-124805 |archivedate=2 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFilms which have publicised issues of beluga welfare include Born to Be Free,<ref name=\"b2bf\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6619064/ |title=Born to Be Free |date=18 July 2017 |access-date=12 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414134603/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6619064/ |archivedate=14 April 2017}}</ref> Sonic Sea,<ref name=\"ss\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wildandscenicfilmfestival.org/film/sonic-sea-2/ |title=Sonic Sea \u2013 Wild & Scenic Film Festival |website=Wild & Scenic Film Festival |access-date=12 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012095625/https://www.wildandscenicfilmfestival.org/film/sonic-sea-2/ |archivedate=12 October 2017}}</ref> and Vancouver Aquarium Uncovered.<ref name=\"vau\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/vancouver-aquarium-sues-filmmaker-over-critical-documentary-1.3452094 |title=Vancouver Aquarium sues filmmaker over critical documentary |last=Proctor |first=Jason |publisher=CBC News |access-date=12 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324084958/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/vancouver-aquarium-sues-filmmaker-over-critical-documentary-1.3452094 |archivedate=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Whale watching ===\n[[File:Beluga Whale Tadoussac Quebec Canada Luca Galuzzi 2005.jpg|thumb|Beluga at the confluence of the [[Saint Lawrence River|Saint Lawrence]] and [[Saguenay River|Saguenay]] rivers]]\n[[Whale watching]] has become an important activity in the recovery of the economies of towns in Quebec and Hudson Bay, near the Saint Lawrence and Churchill Rivers (in fact Churchill is considered to be the Beluga Whale Capital of the World) <ref>5 things you didn't know about Churchill. (2015, February 4). Retrieved from https://frontiersnorth.com/blog/2015/01/5-things-you-didn\u2019t-know-about-churchill</ref>respectively. The best time to see belugas is during the summer, when they meet in large numbers in the estuaries of the rivers and in their summer habitats.<ref name=whatch>{{cite web |url=http://www.chem.ucla.edu/~alice/explorations/churchill/whale.htm |title=Beluga Whale Watching |author=UCLA Department of Chemistry and Biochemistry |accessdate=11 February 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100526090516/http://www.chem.ucla.edu/~alice/explorations/churchill/whale.htm |archivedate=26 May 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The animals are easily seen due to their high numbers and their curiosity regarding the presence of humans.<ref name=whatch />\n\nHowever, the boats' presence poses a threat to the animals, as it distracts them from important activities such as feeding, social interaction and reproduction. In addition, the noise produced by the motors has an adverse effect on their auditory function and reduces their ability to detect their prey, communicate and navigate.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=3718148&q=&uid=789784791&setcookie=yes |author=Blane, JM. |author2=Jackson, R |title=The impact of ecotourism boats on the St. Lawrence beluga whales |journal=Environmental Conservation |volume=21 |issue=3 |year=1994 |pages=267\u2013269 |doi=10.1017/S0376892900033282 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105090523/http://md1.csa.com/partners/viewrecord.php?requester=gs&collection=ENV&recid=3718148&q=&uid=789784791&setcookie=yes |archivedate=5 November 2012}}</ref> To protect these marine animals during whale-watching activities, the US [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] has published a \"Guide for observing marine life\". The guide recommends boats carrying the whale watchers keep their distance from the cetaceans and it expressly prohibits chasing, harassing, obstructing, touching, or feeding them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/pdfs/education/viewing_wildlife.pdf |author=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |title=Marine Wildlife Viewing Guidelines |date=January 2004 |accessdate=6 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617162222/http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/pdfs/education/viewing_wildlife.pdf |archivedate=17 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nSome regular migrations do occur into Russian [[EEZ]] of [[Sea of Japan]] such as to [[:W:\u0420\u0443\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f (\u0431\u0443\u0445\u0442\u0430)|Rudnaya Bay]], where diving with wild belugas became a less-known but popular attraction.<ref>{{cite web |author=Shpatak A. |year=2012 |title=Japan Sea. Rudnaya Bay. Polar White Whale. |url=http://shpatak.35photo.ru/photo_347828/ |publisher=The 35PHOTO.ru |accessdate=19 January 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119095317/http://shpatak.35photo.ru/photo_347828/ |archivedate=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 September 2018, a beluga was sighted in the [[Thames Estuary]] and near towns along the [[Kent]] side of the Thames, being nicknamed [[Benny the Beluga Whale|Benny]] by newspapers. The whale, who was noticed by conservationists to be travelling alone, appeared to be separated from the rest of its group, and is thought to be a lost individual. Subsequent sightings were reported on the following day.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Berg Olsen |first1=Martine |title=Benny the beluga whale spotted swimming in River Thames again |url=https://metro.co.uk/2018/09/26/benny-the-beluga-whale-spotted-swimming-in-river-thames-again-7980284/ |website=Metro|date=2018-09-26 }}</ref>\n\n=== Human speech ===\nMale belugas in captivity can mimic the pattern of human speech, several octaves lower than typical whale calls. It is not the first time a beluga has been known to sound human, and they often shout like children, in the wild.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/10/23/study-male-beluga-whale-mimics-human-speech.html |title=Study: Male beluga whale mimics human speech |date=23 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714191128/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2012/10/23/study-male-beluga-whale-mimics-human-speech.html |archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref> One captive beluga, after overhearing divers using an underwater communication system, caused one of the divers to surface by imitating their order to get out of the water. Subsequent recordings confirmed that the beluga had become skilled at imitating the patterns and frequency of human speech. After several years, this beluga ceased making these sounds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/story-one-whale-who-tried-bridge-linguistic-divide-between-animals-humans-180951437/ |title=The Story of One Whale Who Tried to Bridge the Linguistic Divide Between Animals and Humans |date=June 2014 |work=Smithsonian Magazine}}</ref>\n\n== Conservation status ==\n[[File:Begula White Whale program eng.ogv|thumb|Video explaining conservation efforts in the [[Sea of Okhotsk]], [[Russia]]]]\n[[File:Faroe stamp 329 white whale (Delphinapterus leucas).jpg|thumb|right|Pictured on [[Faroe Islands]] stamp|alt=Photo of stamp showing two adults and one juvenile, swimming]]\nPrior to 2008, the beluga was listed as \"vulnerable\" by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN), a higher level of concern. The IUCN cited the stability of the largest subpopulations and improved census methods that indicate a larger population than previously estimated. In 2008, the beluga was reclassified as \"near threatened\" by the IUCN due to uncertainty about threats to their numbers and the number of belugas over parts of its range (especially the Russian Arctic), and the expectation that if current conservation efforts cease, especially hunting management, the beluga population is likely to qualify for \"threatened\" status within five years.<ref>{{cite iucn |vauthors=Jefferson TA, Karkzmarski L, Laidre K, O'Corry-Crowe G, Reeves R, Rojas-Bracho L, Secchi E, Slooten E, Smith BD, Wang JY, Zhou K |title=''Delphinapterus leucas'' |volume=2012 |page=e.T6335A17690692 |year=2012 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2012.RLTS.T6335A17690692.en }}</ref> In June 2017, its status was reassessed to \"least concern\".<ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |url = https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/6335/0 |title = ''Delphinapterus leucas'' |author = Lowry, L |year = 2017 |access-date = 21 December 2017|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nThere are about 21 subpopulations of beluga whales and it is estimated that 200,000 individuals still exist, which are listed as Least Concern on the IUCN Red List <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/en|title=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species: Beluga|last=Lloyd Lowry (University of Alaska Fairbanks|first=School of Fisheries and Ocean Sciences)|last2=University)|first2=Greg O\u2019Corry-Crowe (Florida Atlantic|date=2018-08-04|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|doi=10.2305/iucn.uk.2019-1.rlts.t61442a50384653.en|access-date=2020-03-15|last3=Hobbs|first3=Roderick}}</ref>. However, the nonmigratory Cook Inlet subpopulation off the Gulf of Alaska is a separate subpopulation that is listed as \"critically endangered\" by the IUCN as of 2006<ref name=iucn /> and as \"endangered\" under the [[Endangered Species Act]] as of October 2008.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE49G6JD20081017 |title=Beluga whales in Alaska listed as endangered |last=Rosen |first=Yereth |date=17 October 2008 |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=17 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020223559/https://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSTRE49G6JD20081017 |archivedate=20 October 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/pdfs/fr/fr73-62919.pdf |title=Endangered and Threatened Species; Endangered Status for the Cook Inlet Beluga Whale |date=22 October 2008 |publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] |accessdate=26 August 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512074741/http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/pdfs/fr/fr73-62919.pdf |archivedate=12 May 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gJx0IzvRt6GWrUBb90Foe4URCGagD93SD0DO0 |title=Government declares beluga whale endangered |last=Herbert |first=H. Josef |date=17 October 2008 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=17 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028200609/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gJx0IzvRt6GWrUBb90Foe4URCGagD93SD0DO0 |archivedate=28 October 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"iucn\" /> This was primarily due to unregulated [[overharvesting]] of beluga whalesprior to 1998. The population has remained relatively consistent, though the reported harvest has been small. As of 2016, the estimated abundance of the endangered Cook Inlet population was 293 individuals. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/feature-story/noaa-releases-new-abundance-estimate-endangered-cook-inlet-beluga-whales|title=NOAA Releases New Abundance Estimate for Endangered Cook Inlet Beluga Whales {{!}} NOAA Fisheries|last=Fisheries|first=NOAA|date=2020-02-03|website=NOAA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The most recent estimate in 2018 by NOAA Fisheries suggested that the population declined to 279 individuals. <ref name=\":1\" />\n\nDespite beluga whales not being threatened overall, subpopulations are being listed as critically endangered and are facing increased mortality from human actions. For example, even though commercial hunting is now banned due to the Marine Mammal Protection Act, beluga whales are still being hunted to preserve the livelihood of native Alaskan communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/species/beluga-whale|title=Beluga Whale {{!}} NOAA Fisheries|last=Fisheries|first=NOAA|date=2020-03-02|website=NOAA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref> The IUCN and NOAA Fisheries cite habitat degradation, oil and gas drilling, underwater noise, harvesting for consumption and climate change as threats to the prolonged survival of beluga whale subpopulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/species/beluga-whale|title=Beluga Whale {{!}} NOAA Fisheries|last=Fisheries|first=NOAA|date=2020-03-02|website=NOAA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nBeluga whale populations are currently being harvested at levels which are not sustainable and it is difficult for those harvesting beluga whales to know which subpopulation they are from.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Laidre|first=K. L.|last2=Stirling|first2=I.|last3=Lowry|first3=L.|last4=Wiig|first4=\u00d8|last5=Heide-J\u00f8rgensen|first5=M. P.|last6=Ferguson|first6=S.|date=2008|title=Quantifying the sensitivity of arctic marine mammals to climate-induced habitat change|journal=Ecological Applications|volume=18|issue=2|pages=S97\u2013S125|doi=10.1890/06-0546.1|pmid=18494365|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/9fff8c993bedb6c02d480c1610a1b1faa83680a1}}</ref> Because there is little protection of subpopulations, harvest will need to be managed to ensure subpopulations will survive long into the future to discover the importance of their migratory patterns and habitat use.\n\nBeluga whales, like most other arctic species, are being faced with alteration of their habitat due to climate change and melting arctic ice.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is hypothesized that beluga whales utilize ice as protection from killer whale predation or for feeding on schools of fish.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucn.org/sites/dev/files/import/downloads/fact_sheet_red_list_beluga_v2.pdf|title=Beluga Whales and Climate Change|last=Liao|first=Bill|date=2009|website=IUCN Red List|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As annual ice cover declines, humans may gain access and disrupt beluga whale habitats.<ref name=\":2\" /> For example, the number of vessels in the Arctic for gas and oil exploration, fishing, and commercial shipping has already increased and a continuous trend may lead to higher risks of injuries and deaths for beluga whales.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn addition, it is possible that beluga whales may face by an increased risk of entrapment from leads and cracks freezing, due to the erratic nature of climate change. Abrupt changes in weather can cause these leads and cracks to freeze ultimately causing the whales to die of suffocation.<ref name=\":0\" /> An increase in urbanization will likely lead to higher concentrations of toxic pollutants in the blubber of beluga whales since they are at the top of the food chain and are affected by bioaccumulation.<ref name=\":2\" /> Finally, loss of sea ice and a change in ocean temperatures may also affect the distribution and composition of prey or affect their competition.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== Legal protection ===\nThe US Congress passed the [[Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972]], outlawing the persecution and hunting of all marine mammals within US coastal waters. The act has been amended a number of times to permit subsistence hunting by native peoples, temporary capture of restricted numbers for research, education and public display, and to decriminalise the accidental capture of individuals during fishing operations.<ref name=\"mmpa\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/pdfs/laws/mmpa.pdf |author=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |title=MMPA \u2013 The Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972 as Amended (2007) |date=January 2004 |accessdate=6 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601145639/http://www.nmfs.noaa.gov/pr/pdfs/laws/mmpa.pdf |archivedate=1 June 2010}}</ref> The act also states that all whales in US territorial waters are under the jurisdiction of the National Marine Fisheries Service, a division of NOAA.<ref name=\"mmpa\" />\n\nTo prevent hunting, belugas are protected under the 1986 International Moratorium on Commercial Whaling; however, hunting of small numbers of belugas is still allowed. Since it is very difficult to know the exact population of belugas because their habitats include inland waters away from the ocean, they easily come in contact with [[oil]] and [[gas]] development centres. To prevent whales from coming in contact with industrial waste, the Alaskan and Canadian governments are relocating sites where whales and waste come in contact.\n\nThe beluga whale is listed on appendix II<ref name=\"Appendices\">\"[http://www.cms.int/documents/appendix/Appendices_COP9_E.pdf Appendix II] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611112003/http://www.cms.int/documents/appendix/Appendices_COP9_E.pdf |date=11 June 2011 }}\" of the Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals (CMS). As amended by the Conference of the Parties in 1985, 1988, 1991, 1994, 1997, 1999, 2002, 2005 and 2008. Effective: 5 March 2009.</ref> of the Convention on the Conservation of Migratory Species of Wild Animals (CMS). It is listed on appendix II<ref name=\"Appendices\" /> as it has an unfavourable conservation status or would benefit significantly from international co-operation organised by tailored agreements. All toothed whales are protected under the [[CITES]] that was signed in 1973 to regulate the commercial exploitation of certain species.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cites.org |title=Official CITES website |publisher=Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora |accessdate=20 December 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091209042111/http://www.cites.org/ |archivedate=9 December 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe isolated beluga population in the Saint Lawrence River has been legally protected since 1983.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/kqed/oceanadventures/episodes/seaghosts/indepth-belugas.html |work=Jean-Michael Cousteau \u2013 Ocean Adventures |author=Shih, Xenia |title=In-depth: Belugas \u2013 Beluga Whales Under Threat |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620002206/http://www.pbs.org/kqed/oceanadventures/episodes/seaghosts/indepth-belugas.html |archivedate=20 June 2017}}</ref> In 1988 [[Fisheries and Oceans Canada|Canadian Department of Fisheries and Oceans]] and [[Environment Canada]], a governmental agency that supervises national parks, implemented the Saint Lawrence Action Plan<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planstlaurent.qc.ca/index_e.html |author=St. Lawrence Action Plan \u2013 Official Page |title=St. Lawrence Action Plan For a Sustainable Development |accessdate=6 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110125142542/http://www.planstlaurent.qc.ca/index_e.html |archivedate=25 January 2011}}</ref> with the aim of reducing industrial contamination by 90% by 1993; as of 1992, the emissions had been reduced by 59%.<ref name=dold /> The population of the St. Lawrence belugas decreased from 10,000 in 1885 to around 1,000 in the 1980 and around 900 in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/species-especes/profiles-profils/belugaStLa-eng.html |title=Beluga Whale (St. Lawrence Estuary population) |publisher=Government of Canada |accessdate=22 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821215337/http://dfo-mpo.gc.ca/species-especes/profiles-profils/belugaStLa-eng.html |archivedate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservation research in managed care facilities ===\nAs of 2015, there were 33 individuals housed in managed care facilities in North America.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Brien|first=J. K.|last2=Robeck|first2=T. R.|date=2010-04-28|title=Preservation of beluga (Delphinapterus leucas) spermatozoa using a trehalose-based cryodiluent and directional freezing technology|url=https://www.publish.csiro.au/rd/RD09176|journal=Reproduction, Fertility and Development|language=en|volume=22|issue=4|pages=653\u2013663|doi=10.1071/RD09176|issn=1448-5990}}</ref> These facilities are members of the Association of Zoos and Aquariums, aiming to understand the complex reproductive physiology of this species to improve their conservation. With the extreme difficulty of studying beluga whales in the wild and the lack of ability to collect biological samples or perform examinations on individuals, managed care facilities play a critical role.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Brien|first=J. K.|last2=Robeck|first2=T. R.|date=2010|title=The Value of Ex Situ Cetacean Populations in Understanding Reproductive Physiology and Developing Assisted Reproductive Technology for Ex Situ and In Situ Species Management and Conservation Efforts|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/1n15q19h|journal=International Journal of Comparative Psychology|language=en|volume=23|issue=3|issn=0889-3667}}</ref> \n\nManaged care facilities in North America have been able to work cooperatively to build upon the research of beluga whale reproduction and have made remarkable advances. Using operant conditioning, these facilities have trained beluga whales for voluntary biological sampling and examinations. Blood<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Katsumata|first=Etsuko|last2=Furuta|first2=Chie|last3=Katsumata|first3=Hiroshi|last4=Watanabe|first4=Gen|last5=Taya|first5=Kazuyoshi|date=2006|title=Basal Body Temperature Method for Detecting Ovarian Cycle in the Captive Beluga (Delphinapterus leucas)|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/jrd/52/1/52_1_59/_article|journal=Journal of Reproduction and Development|volume=52|issue=1|pages=59\u201363|doi=10.1262/jrd.17066|doi-access=free}}</ref>, urine<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Steinman|first=K. J.|last2=O\u2019Brien|first2=J. K.|last3=Monfort|first3=S. L.|last4=Robeck|first4=T. R.|date=2012-02-01|title=Characterization of the estrous cycle in female beluga (Delphinapterus leucas) using urinary endocrine monitoring and transabdominal ultrasound: Evidence of facultative induced ovulation|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0016648011004229|journal=General and Comparative Endocrinology|language=en|volume=175|issue=3|pages=389\u2013397|doi=10.1016/j.ygcen.2011.11.008|issn=0016-6480}}</ref>, and blow samples<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Richard|first=Justin T.|last2=Schmitt|first2=Todd|last3=Haulena|first3=Martin|last4=Vezzi|first4=No\u00ebl|last5=Dunn|first5=J. Lawrence|last6=Romano|first6=Tracy A.|last7=Sartini|first7=Becky L.|date=2017-05-29|title=Seasonal variation in testes size and density detected in belugas (Delphinapterus leucas) using ultrasonography|url=https://academic.oup.com/jmammal/article-lookup/doi/10.1093/jmammal/gyx032|journal=Journal of Mammalogy|language=en|volume=98|issue=3|pages=874\u2013884|doi=10.1093/jmammal/gyx032|issn=0022-2372|doi-access=free}}</ref> have all been collected for longitudinal hormone monitoring studies. \n\nIn addition, beluga whales have undergone voluntary semen collection<ref name=\":3\" />, body temperature data collection<ref name=\":4\" />, reproductive tract examinations via transabdominal ultrasound, and endoscopic exams.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Robeck|first=T. R.|last2=Steinman|first2=K. J.|last3=Montano|first3=G. A.|last4=Katsumata|first4=E.|last5=Osborn|first5=S.|last6=Dalton|first6=L.|last7=Dunn|first7=J. L.|last8=Schmitt|first8=T.|last9=Reidarson|first9=T.|last10=O'Brien|first10=J. K.|date=2010-10-01|title=Deep intra-uterine artificial inseminations using cryopreserved spermatozoa in beluga (Delphinapterus leucas)|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0093691X10002384|journal=Theriogenology|language=en|volume=74|issue=6|pages=989\u20131001|doi=10.1016/j.theriogenology.2010.04.028|issn=0093-691X}}</ref> With new technology, the reproductive characteristics of both the female and male beluga whale have been accurately described and has benefited captive breeding programs globally.\n\nAs more research is done, the management of beluga whales in managed care facilities can be greatly improved and may even help develop other cetacean breeding and contraceptive programs, such as that of the bottlenose dolphin.<ref name=\":3\" /> Through fetal health and gestation monitoring, facilities can be more equipped to deal with pregnant animals as well.<ref name=\":4\" /> While training has been done to collect beluga whale semen, only few facilities have been able to successfully do so as both saltwater and urine contamination need to be avoided.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Brien|first=J. K.|last2=Steinman|first2=K. J.|last3=Schmitt|first3=T.|last4=Robeck|first4=T. R.|date=2008-10-06|title=Semen collection, characterisation and artificial insemination in the beluga (Delphinapterus leucas) using liquid-stored spermatozoa|url=https://www.publish.csiro.au/rd/RD08031|journal=Reproduction, Fertility and Development|language=en|volume=20|issue=7|pages=770\u2013783|doi=10.1071/RD08031|issn=1448-5990}}</ref> Improvement of this process will help increase the success of captive breeding programs.\n\n== Cultural references ==\n[[File:M\u00e2choire de b\u00e9louga grav\u00e9e.JPG|thumb|Engravings on beluga bones]]\n\n''[[Pour la suite du monde]]'', is a Canadian documentary film released in 1963 about traditional beluga hunting carried out by the inhabitants of [[L'Isle-aux-Coudres]] on the Saint Lawrence River.<ref>{{cite web |author=The Internet Movie Database |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0057423 |title=Pour la suite du monde |accessdate=7 August 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100104193336/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0057423/ |archivedate=4 January 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe children's singer [[Raffi (musician)|Raffi]] released an album called ''[[Baby Beluga]]'' in 1980. The album starts with the sound of whales communicating, and includes songs representing the ocean and whales playing. The song \"Baby Beluga\" was composed after Raffi saw a recently born beluga calf in Vancouver Aquarium.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kids.niehs.nih.gov/music.htm#index |publisher=National Institutes of Health |title=Baby beluga |accessdate=12 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527102209/http://kids.niehs.nih.gov/music.htm#index |archivedate=27 May 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe fuselage design of the [[Airbus Beluga]], one of the world's biggest cargo planes, is very similar to that of a beluga. It was originally called the Super Transporter, but the nickname Beluga became more popular and was then officially adopted.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airbus.com/en/services/airtransport/ |title=Airbus beluga service |publisher=airbus.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223224128/http://www.airbus.com/en/services/airtransport/ |archivedate=23 December 2010}}</ref>\nThe company paints the 2019 [[Airbus Beluga XL|Beluga XL]] version to emphasize the plane's similarity to the Beluga whale.<ref name=\"ohare\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/airbus-beluga-xl-first-uk-flight/index.html |title=Beluga XL spreads its wings at long last |last=O'Hare |first=Maureen |date=2019-02-18 |work=CNN |access-date=2019-12-07 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Airbus_Industrie_Airbus_A300B4-608ST_F-GSTF_(8394493208).jpg|thumb|Airbus Beluga]]\n\nIn the 2016 [[Disney]]/[[Pixar]] animated film ''[[Finding Dory]]'', the sequel to ''[[Finding Nemo]]'', the character Bailey is a beluga whale, and its echolocation abilities are a significant part of the plot.<ref name=\"mccarthy\">{{Cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/ty-burrell-makes-splash-whale-finding-dory/story?id=39925024 |title=Ty Burrell Makes a Splash as a Whale in 'Finding Dory' |last=McCarthy |first=Kelly |date=2016-06-17 |work=ABC News |access-date=2019-12-07 |language=en}}</ref>\n<ref name=THRcast>{{cite news |last=Schillaci |first=Sophie |title=D23: Disney Sets Voice Casts for 'Finding Dory,' 'Inside Out' and 'Good Dinosaur' |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/d23-ty-burrell-diane-keaton-603503 |accessdate=9 August 2013 |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |date=9 August 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305135202/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/d23-ty-burrell-diane-keaton-603503 |archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cetaceans|Mammals|Marine life}}\n* [[List of cetacean species]]\n* [[Marine biology]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n|refs =\n<ref name=\"dierauf\">{{cite book |title = CRC Handbook of Marine Mammal Medicine: Health, Disease, and Rehabilitation |last1 = Dierauf |first1 = L. |last2 = Gulland |first2 = F. |lastauthoramp = yes |pages = [https://archive.org/details/crchandbookofmar00dier/page/26 26, 303, 359] |year = 2001 |publisher = CRC Press |isbn = 978-0-8493-0839-0 |url = https://archive.org/details/crchandbookofmar00dier/page/26 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=s8Dolyb5g2sC |page=1}}|title =Beluga days: tracking a white whale's truths|last =Lord|first =Nancy|publisher=Counterpoint|year =2004|isbn=978-1-58243-151-2}}\n* {{cite journal |year=2002 |title=A Comparison of Modern and Preindustrial Levels of Mercury in the Teeth of Beluga in the Mackenzie Delta, Northwest Territories, and Walrus at Igloolik, Nunavut, Canada |journal=Arctic |volume=55 |issue=2 |pages=123\u2013132 |doi=10.14430/arctic696 |author=Outridge P. M. |author2=Hobson K. A. |author3=McNeely R. |author4=Dyke A.|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/cf1cb5be8bc2f177cfd3fc10defb197a96877cd4 }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |editor-first1=William F. |editor-last1=Perrin |editor-first2=Bernd |editor-last2=Wursig |editor-first3=J.G.M. 'Hans' |editor-last3=Thewissen |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Marine Mammals |url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=2rkHQpToi9sC}}|date=26 February 2009|publisher=Academic Press |isbn=978-0-08-091993-5 |ref=harv|title=Encyclopedia of Marine Mammals }}\n{{